{"title_page": "List of Category 1 Australian region tropical cyclones", "text_new": "Category 1 is the lowest classification on the [[Australian tropical cyclone intensity scale]] used to classify tropical cyclones, that have 10-minute sustained winds of {{convert|33\u201347|kn|km/h mph}}. {{As of|2020}} tropical cyclones have peaked as Category 1 tropical cyclones in the South Pacific tropical cyclone basin, which is denoted as the waters surrounding Australia to the south of the equator, between 90\u00b0E and 160\u00b0E. The earliest tropical cyclone to be classified as a Category 1 tropical cyclone was Carmen. The latest was Harold which was classified as a Category 1 tropical cyclone as it moved through the Solomon Sea.\n\n==Background==\nThe [[Australian region tropical cyclone|Australian region tropical cyclone basin]] is located to the south of the [[Equator]] between [[90\u00b0E]] and [[160\u00b0E]].{{RA V Tropical cyclone operational plan}} The basin is officially monitored by the Australian [[Bureau of Meteorology]], Papua New Guinea's National Weather Service as well as Indonesia's [[Badan Meteorologi Klimatologi dan Geofisika]]. Other meteorological services such as the [[Fiji Meteorological Service]], the New Zealand [[MetService]], [[Meteo France]] as well as the United States [[Joint Typhoon Warning Center]] also monitor the basin.<ref name=\"SPAC TCOP\"/> Within the basin a Category 1 tropical cyclone is a [[tropical cyclone]] that has 10-minute mean maximum sustained wind speeds of {{convert|33\u201347|kn|km/h mph}} on the [[Australian tropical cyclone intensity scale]].<ref name=\"SPAC TCOP\"/><ref name=\"TC Procedures\">{{Cite report|url=http://www.met.gov.fj/TC_Procedures.pdf |title=2017/2018 Tropical Cyclone Season Summary of Alerts and Warnings Procedures for Fiji|publisher=Fiji Meteorological Service |publication-date=October 23, 2017 |pages=3 & 11|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/78dlW7gal|archivedate=May 25, 2019}}</ref> A named storm could also be classified as a Category 1 tropical cyclone if it is estimated, to have 1-minute mean maximum sustained wind speeds of between {{convert|64\u201382|kn|km/h mph}} on the [[Saffir-Simpson hurricane wind scale]].<ref name=\"SPAC TCOP\"/><ref name=\"SSHWS\">{{cite report|url=https://www.nhc.noaa.gov/pdf/sshws.pdf|publisher=United States National Hurricane Center|author1=Schott, Timothy|author2=Landsea, Christopher|author3=Hafele, Gene|author4=Lorens, Jeffrey|author5=Taylor, Arthur|author6=Thrum, Harvey|author7=Ward, Bill|author8=Willis, Mark|author9=Zaleski, Walt|date=January 2, 2019|accessdate=June 4, 2019|title=The Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Wind Scale}}</ref> However, this scale is not officially used in the Australian, however, various agencies including NASA also use it to compare tropical cyclones.<ref name=\"SPAC TCOP\"/> A Category 1 tropical cyclone is expected to cause some damage, if it significantly impacts land at or near its peak intensity.<ref name=\"TC Procedures\"/><ref name=\"SSHWS\"/>\n\n==Systems==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Name\n! Dates as a<br/>Category 1 \n! Duration\n! Sustained<br/>wind speeds\n! Pressure\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Land areas affected\n! Damage<br/>(USD)\n! Deaths\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Refs\n|-\n| [[1969\u201370 South Pacific cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Isa|Isa]] || {{Sort|19710210|16&nbsp;\u2013 18 April 1970}} || {{Sort|048|2&nbsp;days}} || {{Sort|075|75&nbsp;km/h (45&nbsp;mph)}} || {{convert|990|hPa|inHg|abbr=on|sigfig=4|sortable=on}} || Solomon Islands || || ||<ref name=\"Isa IBTRACS\">{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=1970104S10164}}|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|title=1970 Tropical Cyclone Isa (1970104S10164)|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Cyclone Dora|Dora]] || {{Sort|19710210|10&nbsp;\u2013 17 February 1971}} || {{Sort|144|6&nbsp;days}} || {{Sort|075|75&nbsp;km/h (45&nbsp;mph)}} || {{convert|990|hPa|inHg|abbr=on|sigfig=4|sortable=on}} || Queensland |