al Cyclone Flamboyan|Flamboyan (2018)]]\n|-\n|  [[2018\u201319 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Kenanga|Kenanga (2019)]]\n|-\n|  [[2018\u201319 Australian region cyclone season#Tropical Cyclone Lili|Lili (2019)]]\n|-\n| [[Cyclone Blake|Blake (2020)]]\n|-\n|  [[Cyclone Esther|Esther (2020)]]\n|-\n|  [[Cyclone Gretel|Gretel (2020)]]\n|-\n|  [[Cyclone Harold|Harold (2020)]]\n|-\n|}\n\n<!-- \n==Other systems==\n\nTropical Cyclone Raquel (2014) developed into a Category 1 tropical cyclone, as it moved out of the region and into the Australian Region.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=February 1, 2020|title=2015 Raquel (2015180S04163)|url={{IBTRACS url|id=2015180S04163}}|publisher=The International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship}}</ref>\n\nThe following 52 systems were estimated to have peaked by the United States [[Joint Typhoon Warning Center]], with 1-minute sustained wind speeds equivalent to a Category 1 hurricane on the SSHWS. The majority of these tropical cyclones peaked as either a Category 2 or Category 3 on the Australian scale. Peni (1980), Sina (1980), Arthur (1981), Cliff, Tahmar, Hettie, Joti, Mark, Nano, William, Freda, Ima, Martin, Sally, Wini, Yali, Dovi, Nancy, Peni, Cliff (1992), Innis (1992), Nina (1992), Nisha (1993), William (1994), Evan (1996), Freda (1996), Hina (1997), June (1997), Nute (1997), Pam (1998), Ursula (1998), Veli (1998), Iris, Jo, Mona, Sose, Claudia, Jim, Vaianu, Wati, Yani, Zita, Arthur, Becky (2007), Mick (2010), Bune (2012), Lusi, Ella (2017), Oma (2019), Rita (2019), Sarai (2019), Tino (2020), Uesi (2020).\nIn addition to the 19 tropical cyclones listed above Severe Tropical Cyclone's: [[Cyclone Harry|Harry]], [[Cyclone Rewa|Rewa]] and [[Cyclone Yasi|Yasi]], all became Category 5 Severe tropical cyclones within the South Pacific Ocean, after they had moved into the [[Australian region tropical cyclone|Australian region]].<ref>{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=1989037S16164}}|title=1989 Severe Tropical Cyclone HARRY (1989037S16164)|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|accessdate=May 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=1993360S04171}}|title=1993 Severe Tropical Cyclone REWA (1993360S04171)|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|accessdate=May 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=2011028S13180}}|title=2011 Severe Tropical Cyclone YASI (2011028S13180)|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|accessdate=May 25, 2019}}</ref> [[Cyclone Anne|Severe Tropical Cyclone Anne]] was estimated to have peaked by the JTWC, with one-minute sustained wind speeds of 260&nbsp;km/h (160&nbsp;mph) for six hours during January 11, 1988.<ref name=\"Anne\">{{cite web|url={{IBTRACS url|id=1988006S05182}}|publisher=International Best Track Archive for Climate Stewardship|title=1988 Tropical Cyclone ANNE (1988006S05182)|accessdate=May 25, 2019}}</ref> This made it equivalent to a Category 5 tropical cyclone on the SSHWS, however, the FMS reported that the system had peaked with 10-minute sustained winds of 185&nbsp;km/h (115&nbsp;mph), which made it a Category 4 severe tropical cyclone on the Australian scale.<ref name=\"Anne\"/> During 2017, a study into Category 4 and 5 tropical cyclones over the South Pacific during the 1980s, was published within the [[Royal Meteorological Society]]'s [[International Journal of Climatology]].<ref name=\"Extreme\">{{cite journal|author1=Hoarau, Karl|author2=Chalonge, Ludovic|author3=Pirard, Florence |author4=Peyrusaubes, Daniel |title=Extreme tropical cyclone activities in the southern Pacific Ocean |journal=International Journal of Climatology |date=March 2018 |volume=38 |issue=3 |pages=1409\u20131420 |doi=10.1002/joc.5254}}</ref> This showed that the intensity of such tropical cyclones had been underestimated by the various warning centres during the decade.<ref name=\"Extreme\"/> In particular, they estimated that Severe Tropical Cyclone's [[Cyclone Oscar|Oscar]] and [[Cyclone Nisha-Orama|Nisha-Orama]] had 1-minute sustained winds of 285&nbsp;km/h (180&nbsp;mph), which would make them Category 5 tropical cyclones on the SSHWS.<ref name=\"Extreme\"/>\n\n==Impacts==\n\n==Records and statistics==\nWithin the official database for the region, as provided by the BoM, FMS and MetService, a total of XX tropical cyclones have been categorised as a Category 3 severe tropical cyclone. The earliest of these was Severe Tropical Cyclone Pam, which was estimated to have been a Category 5 severe tropical cyclone after a reanalysis of the data was performed by the BoM.{{BoM TC Database}} The strongest and most intense of these was Severe Tropical Cyclone Winston of the 2015-16 season, which was estimated to have 10-minute sustained wind speeds of 280&nbsp;km/h (175&nbsp;mph) and a minimum pressure of {{convert|884|hPa|inHg|sigfig=4|abbr=on}} at its peak intensity. Severe Tropical Cyclone Susan maintained its Category 5 status for around 72&nbsp;hours and was the system that maintained its Category 5 status the longest.\n -->\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"nb\"}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Category 1 Atlantic hurricanes]]\n*[[List of Category 1 Pacific hurricanes]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{SPAC EL's}}\n{{Tropical cyclones by intensity}}\n{{Category 1 Australian region tropical cyclones}}\n\n[[Category:Category 1 Australian region cyclones]]\n[[Category:Tropical cyclone intensity articles]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: Norhtern \u2192 Northern, offically \u2192 officially", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Category_1_Australian_region_tropical_cyclones"}
{"title_page": "Gulf of California", "text_new": "{{short description|A gulf of the Pacific Ocean between the Baja peninsula and the Mexican mainland}}\n{{redirect|Sea of Cortez|the John Steinbeck book|The Log from the Sea of Cortez}}\n{{Infobox body of water\n|name= Gulf of California\n|image= Wpdms nasa topo gulf of california.jpg\n|caption = The Gulf of California (highlighted)\n|location= \n|coords= {{Coord|28|0|N|112|0|W|region:MX_type:waterbody_scale:5000000|display=inline,title}}\n|rivers= [[Colorado River|Colorado]], [[Fuerte River|Fuerte]], [[Mayo River (Mexico)|Mayo]], [[Sinaloa River|Sinaloa]], [[Sonora River|Sonora]], and the [[Yaqui River|Yaqui]]\n|oceans= Pacific Ocean\n|depth= \n|countries= [[Mexico]]\n|length= {{convert|1126|km|abbr=on}}\n|width= {{convert|48|-|241|km|abbr=on}}\n|area={{convert|160000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n|settlements= \n|frozen=\n|islands= 37\n|reference=<ref name=\"Nix\"/>\n|extra = {{designation list | embed=yes\n   | designation1 = WHS\n   | designation1_offname = Islands and Protected Areas of the Gulf of California\n   | designation1_date = 2005\n   | designation1_type = Natural\n   | designation1_criteria = vii, ix, x\n   | designation1_number = [https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1182 1182]\n   | designation1_free1name = State Party\n   | designation1_free1value = Mexico\n   | designation1_free2name = Region\n   | designation1_free2value = [[List of World Heritage Sites in the Americas|Latin America and the Caribbean]]\n   | designation1_free3name = [[List of World Heritage in Danger|Endangered]]\n   | designation1_free3value = 2019\u2013present<ref name=\"whs danger\"/>\n  }}\n}}\n\nThe '''Gulf of California''' (also known as the '''Sea of Cortez''', '''Sea of Cort\u00e9s''' (named for Spanish Conquistador [[Hern\u00e1n Cort\u00e9s]]) or '''Vermilion Sea'''; locally known in the [[Spanish language]] as '''Mar de Cort\u00e9s''' or '''Mar Bermejo''' or '''Golfo de California''') is a [[marginal sea]] of the [[Pacific Ocean]] that separates the [[Baja California Peninsula]] from the [[Mexico|Mexican]] mainland. It is bordered by the [[States of Mexico|states]] of [[Baja California]], [[Baja California Sur]], [[Sonora]], and [[Sinaloa]] with a coastline of approximately {{convert|4000|km|mi|abbr=on}}. Rivers which flow into the Gulf of California include the [[Colorado River|Colorado]], [[Fuerte River|Fuerte]], [[Mayo River (Mexico)|Mayo]], [[Sinaloa River|Sinaloa]], [[Sonora River|Sonora]], and the [[Yaqui River|Yaqui]]. The gulf's surface area is about {{convert|160000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}. Depths range from near-zero at its fording at the estuary near [[Yuma, Arizona]], to in excess of {{convert|3000|m|sp=us}} in the deepest parts. <ref name=\"Brusca\"/>\n\nThe Gulf is thought to be one of the most diverse seas on Earth, and is home to more than 5,000 species of micro-invertebrates.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Ernesto Campos, Alma Rosa de Campos & Jes\u00fas Angel de Le\u00f3n-Gonz\u00e1lez |title=Diversity and ecological remarks of ectocommensals and ectoparasites (Annelida, Crustacea, Mollusca) of echinoids (Echinoidea: Mellitidae) in the Sea of Cortez, Mexico |journal=[[Parasitology Research]] |volume=105 |issue=2 |year=2009 |pages=479\u2013487 |doi=10.1007/s00436-009-1419-8|pmid=19337754 }}</ref> Parts of the Gulf of California are a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]].\n\n==Geography==\n;Area\nThe [[International Hydrographic Organization]] defines the southern limit of the Gulf of California as: \"A line joining Piaxtla Point (latitude 23\u00b038'N) on the west coast of the mainland of Mexico, and the southern extreme of [[Baja California Peninsula|Lower California]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iho.int/iho_pubs/standard/S-23/S-23_Ed3_1953_EN.pdf|title=Limits of Oceans and Seas, 3rd edition|year=1953|publisher=[[International Hydrographic Organization]]|page=35|access-date=2016-10-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008191433/http://www.iho-ohi.net/iho_pubs/standard/S-23/S23_1953.pdf|archive-date=2011-10-08|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe Gulf of California is {{convert|1126|km|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|48|-|241|km|abbr=on}} wide, with an area of {{convert|177000|km2|abbr=on}}, a mean depth of {{convert|818.08|m|abbr=on}}, and a volume of {{convert|145000|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Nix\">{{cite web |title=The Gulf of California: A Physical, Geological, and Biological Study |author=Rebekah K. Nix |url=http://www.utdallas.edu/~rnix/MAT-SE_Units/gulf_cal.pdf |publisher=University of Texas at Dallas |accessdate=April 10, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Gulf of California includes three faunal regions:\n\n# the Northern Gulf of California\n# the Central Gulf of California\n# the Southern Gulf of California\n\nOne recognized transition zone is termed the Southwestern Baja California Peninsula. Transition zones exist between faunal regions, and they usually vary for each individual species. (Faunal regions are distinguishable based on the specific types of animals found there.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Gulf of California Invertebrate Database: The Invertebrate Portion of the Macrofauna Golfo Database |publisher=[[Arizona-Sonora Desert Museum]]: Center for Sonoran Desert Studies |url=http://www.desertmuseum.org/center/seaofcortez/database.php}}\n</ref>)\n\n;Geology\n[[File:Gulf of California.jpg|300px|thumbnail|Satellite picture of gulf.]]\nGeologic evidence is widely interpreted by geologists as indicating the Gulf of California came into being around 5.3 million years ago as [[plate tectonics|tectonic forces]] rifted the [[Baja California Peninsula]] off the [[North American Plate]].<ref>[[Warren B. Hamilton|Hamilton, W.B.]], 1961, Origin of the Gulf of California: GSA Bull., 72, 1307\u20131318.</ref> As part of this process, the [[East Pacific Rise]] propagated up the middle of the Gulf along the seabed. This extension of the East Pacific Rise is often referred to as the [[Gulf of California Rift Zone]].  The Gulf would extend as far as [[Indio, California]], except for the tremendous [[river delta|delta]] created by the [[Colorado River]]. This delta blocks the sea from flooding the [[Mexicali]] and [[Imperial Valley]]s. Volcanism dominates the [[East Pacific Rise]]. The island of [[Tortuga Island, Baja California Sur|Isla Tortuga]] is one example of this ongoing volcanic activity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://review.nsf-margins.org/SPRCL.html |title=Science Plans RCL |publisher=review.nsf-margins.org |accessdate=May 27, 2008}}</ref> Furthermore, [[hydrothermal vent]]s due to extension tectonic regime, related to the opening of the Gulf of California, are found in the Bah\u00eda de Concepci\u00f3n, Baja California Sur.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Leal-Acosta, M.L., Prol-Ledesma, R.M.|year=2016|title=Caracterizaci\u00f3n geoqu\u00edmica de las manifestaciones termales intermareales de Bah\u00eda Concepci\u00f3n en la Pen\u00ednsula de Baja California|journal=Bolet\u00edn de la Sociedad Geol\u00f3gica Mexicana|language=Spanish|volume=68|issue=3|pages=395\u2013407|doi=10.18268/BSGM2016v68n3a2}}</ref>\n\n;Islands\n{{see also|List of islands of Mexico#Gulf of California}}\nThe Gulf of California contains 37 major islands \u2013 the two largest being [[Isla \u00c1ngel de la Guarda]] and [[Tibur\u00f3n Island]]. Most of the islands are found on the peninsular side of the gulf. In fact, many of the islands of the Sea of Cortez are the result of volcanic explosions that occurred during the early history of Baja California. The islands of [[Islas Mar\u00edas]], Islas San Francisco, and [[Isla Partida]] are thought to be the result of such explosions. The formations of the islands, however, are not dependent on each other. They were each formed as a result of an individual structural occurrence.<ref name=\"Brusca\"/> Several islands, including [[Isla Coronados]], are home to volcanoes.\n\nThe gulf has more than 900 islets and islands which together total about 420 hectares. All of them as a whole were enacted as \"Area Reserve and Migratory Bird Refuge and Wildlife\" on August 2, 1978. In June 2000, the islands were given a new category \"Protection Area Wildlife\". In addition to this effort by the Mexican government, for its importance and recognition worldwide, all islands in the Gulf of California are also part of the international program \"Man and Biosphere\" (MAB) and are part of the World Reserve Network UNESCO Biosphere as Special Biosphere Reserve. Due to the vast expanse covered by this federal protected area conservation and management is carried out through a system of four regional directorates (one per bordering the Gulf of California state) by way of co-direction. There is a regional directorate in the states of Baja California, Baja California Sur, Sonora and Sinaloa. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the work of direct and indirect conservation is done in the islands is governed by a single Management Program, published in 2000, which is complemented by local and specific management programs (at individuals) archipelagos. The Directorate of Protection Area Wildlife California Gulf Islands (APFF-GCR) in Baja California is responsible for 56 islands located off the coast of the state. These are grouped into four archipelagos: San Luis Gonzaga or Enchanted, Guardian Angel, Bahia de los Angeles and San Lorenzo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mexicodesconocido.com.mx/valle-de-los-cirios.-tesoro-de-baja-california.html|title=Valle de los Cirios. Tesoro de Baja California|date=14 July 2010|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://islasgc.conanp.gob.mx/islas/|title=\u00c1rea de Protecci\u00f3n de Flora y Fauna Islas del Golfo de California en Baja California|publisher=|access-date=2016-06-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150328022637/http://islasgc.conanp.gob.mx/islas/|archive-date=2015-03-28|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n;Shores and tides\nThe three general types of shores found in the Gulf of California include [[rocky shore]], sandy beach, and tidal flat. Some of the rich biodiversity and high [[endemism]] that characterize the Gulf of California and make it such a hotspot for fishing can be attributed to seemingly insignificant factors, such as the types of rocks that make up a shore. Beaches with softer, more porous rocks (such as Coquina limestone, rhyolites, granite, or diorite) generally have a higher species richness than those with harder, smoother rocks (such as basalt or diabase). Porous rocks will naturally have more cracks and crevices in them, making them ideal living spaces for many animals. The rocks themselves, however, generally need to be stable on the shore for a habitat to be stable. Additionally, the color of the rocks can affect the organisms living on a shore. For example, darker rocks will be significantly warmer than lighter ones, and can deter animals that do not have a high tolerance for heat.<ref name=\"Brusca\"/>\nThe northern Gulf of California experiences tidal ranges of up to {{convert|5|m|abbr=on}}. Mixed [[semidiurnal tides]] are the norm throughout most of the Gulf.\n\n;Estuaries\nIn the Gulf of California, there are a number of negative [[estuary|estuaries]], that is, ones in which the [[evaporation]] of seawater is relatively greater than that of the fresh water input. The salinities of these inlets are higher than that of the [[ocean]]. The temperatures, [[Poikilotherm#Ecological niches|poikilothermal]], of these negative [[estuary|estuaries]] also are higher than the general temperature of the Gulf.\n\nIt is possible that at one time these estuaries were positive, that is, ones in which the [[seawater]] component is [[Concentration|diluted]]; therefore, the water is [[brackish water|brackish]], with salinity less than that of the ocean.\n\nHowever, due to human settlement around the Gulf of California and water diversion for municipal and agricultural use in an area of comparatively low rainfall, there are no longer many rivers that freely empty into the Gulf of California. The upper [[Colorado River Delta]] is one example of a historically major estuary and [[wetlands]] [[ecosystem]], that since the 20th century construction of upriver dams and diversion aqueducts on the [[Colorado River]], is now a small [[ephemeral]] remnant estuary. The remaining Gulf inlets still are important to several species of fishes, [[crustacean]]s, and [[shellfish]] that are commercially harvested.<ref name=\"Brusca\"/>\n\n==History==\n\n==Climate==\n;Air\nEven though the shores of the Gulf of California are generally sheltered from the continuous wave shock that is experienced by most other North American shores, storms known as a \"[[chubasco]]\" can cause significant damage to shorelines, despite their brevity.<ref name=\"Brusca\"/>\n\n;Ocean\nThe depth of the water helps to determine its temperature. For example, shallow depths are directly influenced by the local temperature of the air, while deeper waters are less susceptible to changes in air temperature.<ref name=\"Brusca\"/> The temperature of the water in the Gulf of California generally experiences lows of {{convert|16|\u00b0C|abbr=on}} in winter and highs of {{convert|24|\u00b0C|abbr=on}} in summer. But temperatures can vary greatly in the gulf, and the water is almost always warmer by the coast than the open ocean. For example, the waters surrounding La Paz reach {{convert|30|\u00b0C|abbr=on}} in August, while the waters in neighboring city Cabo San Lucas, only reach {{convert|26|\u00b0C|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Nix\"/><ref name=\"deepmexico.com\">[http://www.deepmexico.com/es/ocean_dives.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111221075834/http://www.deepmexico.com/es/ocean_dives.html |date=December 21, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"redalyc.uaemex.mx\">{{cite web |url=http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/html/479/47942204/47942204.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-06-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120715160509/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/html/479/47942204/47942204.html |archivedate=2012-07-15 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://math.ucr.edu/ftm/bajaPages/MarineBiology.html |title=Marine Biology of Baja California |publisher=Math.ucr.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-12-08}}</ref>\n\nOccasionally, the northern Gulf of California will go through significantly cold winters. The water in the Northern Gulf can sometimes drop below {{convert|8|\u00b0C|abbr=on}}, which can lead to a large die-off of marine organisms. The animals most susceptible to the large decrease in water temperature include macroscopic algae and plankton.<ref name=\"Brusca\"/>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Average sea temperatures of [[Puerto Pe\u00f1asco]]<ref name=\"redalyc.uaemex.mx\"/>\n|-\n!'''Jan'''\n!'''Feb'''\n!'''Mar'''\n!'''Apr'''\n!'''May'''\n!'''Jun'''\n!'''Jul'''\n!'''Aug'''\n!'''Sep'''\n!'''Oct'''\n!'''Nov'''\n!'''Dec'''\n|-\n|17&nbsp;\u00b0C\n63&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|16&nbsp;\u00b0C\n61&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|17&nbsp;\u00b0C\n63&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|19&nbsp;\u00b0C\n66&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|21&nbsp;\u00b0C\n70&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|23&nbsp;\u00b0C\n73&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|26&nbsp;\u00b0C\n79&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|28&nbsp;\u00b0C\n82&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|28&nbsp;\u00b0C\n82&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|26&nbsp;\u00b0C\n79&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|23&nbsp;\u00b0C\n73&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|19&nbsp;\u00b0C\n66&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Average sea temperatures of [[La Paz, Baja California Sur|La Paz]]<ref name=\"deepmexico.com\"/>\n|-\n!'''Jan'''\n!'''Feb'''\n!'''Mar'''\n!'''Apr'''\n!'''May'''\n!'''Jun'''\n!'''Jul'''\n!'''Aug'''\n!'''Sep'''\n!'''Oct'''\n!'''Nov'''\n!'''Dec'''\n|-\n|19&nbsp;\u00b0C\n66&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|19&nbsp;\u00b0C\n66&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|21&nbsp;\u00b0C\n70&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|23&nbsp;\u00b0C\n73&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|25&nbsp;\u00b0C\n77&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|27&nbsp;\u00b0C\n81&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|28&nbsp;\u00b0C\n82&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|30&nbsp;\u00b0C\n85&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|28&nbsp;\u00b0C\n82&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|27&nbsp;\u00b0C\n81&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|24&nbsp;\u00b0C\n75&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|21&nbsp;\u00b0C\n70&nbsp;\u00b0F\n\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Average sea temperatures of [[Cabo San Lucas]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.surf-forecast.com/breaks/San-Jorge/seatemp |title=San Jorge Water Temperature (Sea) and Wetsuit Guide (Baja Sur, Mexico) |publisher=Surf-forecast.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-08}}</ref>\n|-\n!'''Jan'''\n!'''Feb'''\n!'''Mar'''\n!'''Apr'''\n!'''May'''\n!'''Jun'''\n!'''Jul'''\n!'''Aug'''\n!'''Sep'''\n!'''Oct'''\n!'''Nov'''\n!'''Dec'''\n|-\n|20&nbsp;\u00b0C\n68&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|19&nbsp;\u00b0C\n66&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|19&nbsp;\u00b0C\n66&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|19&nbsp;\u00b0C\n66&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|20&nbsp;\u00b0C\n68&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|21&nbsp;\u00b0C\n70&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|24&nbsp;\u00b0C\n75&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|26&nbsp;\u00b0C\n79&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|26&nbsp;\u00b0C\n79&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|26&nbsp;\u00b0C\n79&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|24&nbsp;\u00b0C\n75&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|22&nbsp;\u00b0C\n72&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|}\n\n==Marine life==\n[[File:Giant pacific manta.jpg|left|frame|Giant Pacific [[manta ray]]]]\nThe narrow sea is home to a rich ecosystem. In addition to a wide range of [[endemic (ecology)|endemic]] creatures, such as the critically endangered [[vaquita]], it hosts many migratory species, such as the [[humpback whale]], [[California gray whale]], [[killer whale]], [[manta ray]], [[Humboldt squid]] and [[leatherback sea turtle]], and the world's largest animal, the [[blue whale]]. The unusual resident populations of [[fin whale]]s and [[sperm whale]]s do not migrate annually. The area near the delta of the Colorado river has a small remnant population of the [[totoaba]] fish. This region has historically been a magnet for world-class sport [[fishing]] activities, with a rich history of sporting world records.\n\nThe region also has a rich history as a commercial [[fishery]]. However, the data vary wildly according to the species being studied, and the Gulf's ability to recuperate after years of overfishing remains uncertain. Moreover, changes in terrestrial ecology, such as the vast reduction in flow from the Colorado River into the Gulf, have negatively affected fisheries, particularly in the northern region.\n\nThe Gulf of California sustains a large number of marine mammals, many of which are rare and endangered. Its more than 900 islands are important nesting sites for thousands of seabirds, and its waters are primary breeding, feeding, and nursing grounds for myriad migratory and resident fish species. For decades, the gulf has been a primary source of two of Mexico's leading marine resources, sardines and anchovies. Water pollution is a problem in the Gulf of California, but the more immediate concerns are overfishing and bottom trawling, which destroys eelgrass beds and shellfish.\n\nEfforts by the Mexican government to create [[Conservation ethic|conservation zones]] and [[nature reserve]]s have been hampered by lack of enforcement resources, as well as a lack of a political consensus on this issue of conservation of the Gulf.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}} This occurs even though significant areas are a [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]]. The thousands of miles of coastline are remote and difficult to police, and the politically powerful commercial fishing industry has been slow to embrace even economically viable conservation measures, much less strict measures of conservation. Conservation of the Gulf's fisheries and coastlines is also complicated by a long history of overcapitalization in the sector, and the direct, often negative, impacts that conservation measures have on the livelihoods of Mexico's coastal inhabitants. At present, the Mexican government and business interests have promoted a macro-level, tourist development vision for the Gulf, the impacts of which on local ecology and society are uncertain. In 2019, the gulf was added to the [[List of World Heritage in Danger]] because of concerns of the imminent extinction of the [[vaquita]], an endemic porpoise in the area.<ref name=\"whs danger\">{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/1999 |title=The Islands and Protected Areas of the Gulf of California (Mexico) inscribed on the List of World Heritage in Danger |publisher=UNESCO |accessdate=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nCoastal communities are highly reliant on both commercial and sport fishing, including [[San Felipe, Baja California|San Felipe]], [[San Carlos, Sonora]], [[Cabo San Lucas]], [[La Paz, Baja California Sur|La Paz]], [[Loreto, Baja California Sur|Loreto]], [[Guaymas]], [[Bah\u00eda Kino]], [[Puerto Pe\u00f1asco]], [[Topolobampo]] and [[Muleg\u00e9]]. The well-developed shrimp and sardine fleets of [[Mazatl\u00e1n]], on the Mexican mainland's Pacific coast, heavily exploit the commercial fisheries of the southern Gulf.\n\nMany marine organisms can only survive within a particular [[salinity]] range, which makes salinity a notable factor in determining the types of potentially commercial organisms found in the Gulf of California. The mean annual ranges of salinity of the Sea of Cortez are between 3.5 and 3.58% at the surface.<ref name=\"Nix\"/> Furthermore, the salinity of the water of the Northern Gulf of California is generally higher than the Central and Southern faunal regions due to the increased amount of evaporation that occurs in that region.<ref name=\"Brusca\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of western shore communities on the Gulf of California]]\n* [[List of eastern shore communities on the Gulf of California]] \n* [[Ferdinand Kon\u0161\u010dak]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author=Brusca, Richard C. (Editor)|title=The Gulf of California: Biodiversity and Conservation|publisher=University of Arizona Press|date= 2010|pages=354 pages}} Studies by researchers, on both sides of the border, on the threats to the diversity of species in the gulf's waters.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikisource}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20151103082949/http://cedointercultural.org/ CEDO Intercultural]\n* [http://www.desertmuseum.org/center/seaofcortez/ Desert Museum]\n* [http://bajaex.com/protect-wild-baja/ Friends of Wild Baja conserves and protects the critical habitats and biodiversity of The Gulf of California]\n \n{{List of seas}}\n{{coastal geography}}\n{{World Heritage Sites in M\u00e9xico}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gulf Of California}}\n[[Category:Gulf of California| ]]\n[[Category:Gulfs of Mexico|California]]\n[[Category:Gulfs of the Pacific Ocean|California, Gulf of]]\n[[Category:Pacific Coast of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Baja California]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Baja California Sur]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Sonora]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Sinaloa]]\n[[Category:Colorado River]]\n[[Category:Ecoregions of Mexico]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Cenozoic Mexico]]\n[[Category:Cenozoic rifts and grabens]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|A gulf of the Pacific Ocean between the Baja peninsula and the Mexican mainland}}\n{{redirect|Sea of Cortez|the John Steinbeck book|The Log from the Sea of Cortez}}\n{{Infobox body of water\n|name= Gulf of California\n|image= Wpdms nasa topo gulf of california.jpg\n|caption = The Gulf of California (highlighted)\n|location= \n|coords= {{Coord|28|0|N|112|0|W|region:MX_type:waterbody_scale:5000000|display=inline,title}}\n|rivers= [[Colorado River|Colorado]], [[Fuerte River|Fuerte]], [[Mayo River (Mexico)|Mayo]], [[Sinaloa River|Sinaloa]], [[Sonora River|Sonora]], and the [[Yaqui River|Yaqui]]\n|oceans= Pacific Ocean\n|depth= \n|countries= [[Mexico]]\n|length= {{convert|1126|km|abbr=on}}\n|width= {{convert|48|-|241|km|abbr=on}}\n|area={{convert|160000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n|settlements= \n|frozen=\n|islands= 37\n|reference=<ref name=\"Nix\"/>\n|extra = {{designation list | embed=yes\n   | designation1 = WHS\n   | designation1_offname = Islands and Protected Areas of the Gulf of California\n   | designation1_date = 2005\n   | designation1_type = Natural\n   | designation1_criteria = vii, ix, x\n   | designation1_number = [https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1182 1182]\n   | designation1_free1name = State Party\n   | designation1_free1value = Mexico\n   | designation1_free2name = Region\n   | designation1_free2value = [[List of World Heritage Sites in the Americas|Latin America and the Caribbean]]\n   | designation1_free3name = [[List of World Heritage in Danger|Endangered]]\n   | designation1_free3value = 2019\u2013present<ref name=\"whs danger\"/>\n  }}\n}}\n\nThe '''Gulf of California''' (also known as the '''Sea of Cortez''', '''Sea of Cort\u00e9s''' (named for Spanish Conquistador [[Hern\u00e1n Cort\u00e9s]]) or '''Vermilion Sea'''; locally known in the [[Spanish language]] as '''Mar de Cort\u00e9s''' or '''Mar Bermejo''' or '''Golfo de California''') is a [[marginal sea]] of the [[Pacific Ocean]] that separates the [[Baja California Peninsula]] from the [[Mexico|Mexican]] mainland. It is bordered by the [[States of Mexico|states]] of [[Baja California]], [[Baja California Sur]], [[Sonora]], and [[Sinaloa]] with a coastline of approximately {{convert|4000|km|mi|abbr=on}}. Rivers which flow into the Gulf of California include the [[Colorado River|Colorado]], [[Fuerte River|Fuerte]], [[Mayo River (Mexico)|Mayo]], [[Sinaloa River|Sinaloa]], [[Sonora River|Sonora]], and the [[Yaqui River|Yaqui]]. The gulf's surface area is about {{convert|160000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}. Depths range from near-zero at its fording at the estuary near [[Yuma, Arizona]], to in excess of {{convert|3000|m|sp=us}} in the deepest parts. <ref name=\"Brusca\"/>\n\nThe Gulf is thought to be one of the most diverse seas on Earth, and is home to more than 5,000 species of micro-invertebrates.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Ernesto Campos, Alma Rosa de Campos & Jes\u00fas Angel de Le\u00f3n-Gonz\u00e1lez |title=Diversity and ecological remarks of ectocommensals and ectoparasites (Annelida, Crustacea, Mollusca) of echinoids (Echinoidea: Mellitidae) in the Sea of Cortez, Mexico |journal=[[Parasitology Research]] |volume=105 |issue=2 |year=2009 |pages=479\u2013487 |doi=10.1007/s00436-009-1419-8|pmid=19337754 }}</ref> Home to over a million people, Baja California is the second-longest peninsula in the world, after the [[Malay Peninsula]] in Southeast Asia.<ref name=\"Brusca\">{{cite book |author=Richard C. Brusca |title=A Handbook to the Common Intertidal Invertebrates of the Gulf of California |location=Tucson, Arizona |publisher=University of Arizona Press |year=1973 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/handbooktocommon00brus/page/10 10\u201315] |isbn=978-0-8165-0356-8 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/handbooktocommon00brus/page/10 }}</ref> Parts of the Gulf of California are a [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]].\n\n==Geography==\n;Area\nThe [[International Hydrographic Organization]] defines the southern limit of the Gulf of California as: \"A line joining Piaxtla Point (latitude 23\u00b038'N) on the west coast of the mainland of Mexico, and the southern extreme of [[Baja California Peninsula|Lower California]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iho.int/iho_pubs/standard/S-23/S-23_Ed3_1953_EN.pdf|title=Limits of Oceans and Seas, 3rd edition|year=1953|publisher=[[International Hydrographic Organization]]|page=35|access-date=2016-10-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008191433/http://www.iho-ohi.net/iho_pubs/standard/S-23/S23_1953.pdf|archive-date=2011-10-08|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe Gulf of California is {{convert|1126|km|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|48|-|241|km|abbr=on}} wide, with an area of {{convert|177000|km2|abbr=on}}, a mean depth of {{convert|818.08|m|abbr=on}}, and a volume of {{convert|145000|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Nix\">{{cite web |title=The Gulf of California: A Physical, Geological, and Biological Study |author=Rebekah K. Nix |url=http://www.utdallas.edu/~rnix/MAT-SE_Units/gulf_cal.pdf |publisher=University of Texas at Dallas |accessdate=April 10, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Gulf of California includes three faunal regions:\n\n# the Northern Gulf of California\n# the Central Gulf of California\n# the Southern Gulf of California\n\nOne recognized transition zone is termed the Southwestern Baja California Peninsula. Transition zones exist between faunal regions, and they usually vary for each individual species. (Faunal regions are distinguishable based on the specific types of animals found there.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Gulf of California Invertebrate Database: The Invertebrate Portion of the Macrofauna Golfo Database |publisher=[[Arizona-Sonora Desert Museum]]: Center for Sonoran Desert Studies |url=http://www.desertmuseum.org/center/seaofcortez/database.php}}\n</ref>)\n\n;Geology\n[[File:Gulf of California.jpg|300px|thumbnail|Satellite picture of gulf.]]\nGeologic evidence is widely interpreted by geologists as indicating the Gulf of California came into being around 5.3 million years ago as [[plate tectonics|tectonic forces]] rifted the [[Baja California Peninsula]] off the [[North American Plate]].<ref>[[Warren B. Hamilton|Hamilton, W.B.]], 1961, Origin of the Gulf of California: GSA Bull., 72, 1307\u20131318.</ref> As part of this process, the [[East Pacific Rise]] propagated up the middle of the Gulf along the seabed. This extension of the East Pacific Rise is often referred to as the [[Gulf of California Rift Zone]].  The Gulf would extend as far as [[Indio, California]], except for the tremendous [[river delta|delta]] created by the [[Colorado River]]. This delta blocks the sea from flooding the [[Mexicali]] and [[Imperial Valley]]s. Volcanism dominates the [[East Pacific Rise]]. The island of [[Tortuga Island, Baja California Sur|Isla Tortuga]] is one example of this ongoing volcanic activity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://review.nsf-margins.org/SPRCL.html |title=Science Plans RCL |publisher=review.nsf-margins.org |accessdate=May 27, 2008}}</ref> Furthermore, [[hydrothermal vent]]s due to extension tectonic regime, related to the opening of the Gulf of California, are found in the Bah\u00eda de Concepci\u00f3n, Baja California Sur.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Leal-Acosta, M.L., Prol-Ledesma, R.M.|year=2016|title=Caracterizaci\u00f3n geoqu\u00edmica de las manifestaciones termales intermareales de Bah\u00eda Concepci\u00f3n en la Pen\u00ednsula de Baja California|journal=Bolet\u00edn de la Sociedad Geol\u00f3gica Mexicana|language=Spanish|volume=68|issue=3|pages=395\u2013407|doi=10.18268/BSGM2016v68n3a2}}</ref>\n\n;Islands\n{{see also|List of islands of Mexico#Gulf of California}}\nThe Gulf of California contains 37 major islands \u2013 the two largest being [[Isla \u00c1ngel de la Guarda]] and [[Tibur\u00f3n Island]]. Most of the islands are found on the peninsular side of the gulf. In fact, many of the islands of the Sea of Cortez are the result of volcanic explosions that occurred during the early history of Baja California. The islands of [[Islas Mar\u00edas]], Islas San Francisco, and [[Isla Partida]] are thought to be the result of such explosions. The formations of the islands, however, are not dependent on each other. They were each formed as a result of an individual structural occurrence.<ref name=\"Brusca\"/> Several islands, including [[Isla Coronados]], are home to volcanoes.\n\nThe gulf has more than 900 islets and islands which together total about 420 hectares. All of them as a whole were enacted as \"Area Reserve and Migratory Bird Refuge and Wildlife\" on August 2, 1978. In June 2000, the islands were given a new category \"Protection Area Wildlife\". In addition to this effort by the Mexican government, for its importance and recognition worldwide, all islands in the Gulf of California are also part of the international program \"Man and Biosphere\" (MAB) and are part of the World Reserve Network UNESCO Biosphere as Special Biosphere Reserve. Due to the vast expanse covered by this federal protected area conservation and management is carried out through a system of four regional directorates (one per bordering the Gulf of California state) by way of co-direction. There is a regional directorate in the states of Baja California, Baja California Sur, Sonora and Sinaloa. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the work of direct and indirect conservation is done in the islands is governed by a single Management Program, published in 2000, which is complemented by local and specific management programs (at individuals) archipelagos. The Directorate of Protection Area Wildlife California Gulf Islands (APFF-GCR) in Baja California is responsible for 56 islands located off the coast of the state. These are grouped into four archipelagos: San Luis Gonzaga or Enchanted, Guardian Angel, Bahia de los Angeles and San Lorenzo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mexicodesconocido.com.mx/valle-de-los-cirios.-tesoro-de-baja-california.html|title=Valle de los Cirios. Tesoro de Baja California|date=14 July 2010|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://islasgc.conanp.gob.mx/islas/|title=\u00c1rea de Protecci\u00f3n de Flora y Fauna Islas del Golfo de California en Baja California|publisher=|access-date=2016-06-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150328022637/http://islasgc.conanp.gob.mx/islas/|archive-date=2015-03-28|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n;Shores and tides\nThe three general types of shores found in the Gulf of California include [[rocky shore]], sandy beach, and tidal flat. Some of the rich biodiversity and high [[endemism]] that characterize the Gulf of California and make it such a hotspot for fishing can be attributed to seemingly insignificant factors, such as the types of rocks that make up a shore. Beaches with softer, more porous rocks (such as Coquina limestone, rhyolites, granite, or diorite) generally have a higher species richness than those with harder, smoother rocks (such as basalt or diabase). Porous rocks will naturally have more cracks and crevices in them, making them ideal living spaces for many animals. The rocks themselves, however, generally need to be stable on the shore for a habitat to be stable. Additionally, the color of the rocks can affect the organisms living on a shore. For example, darker rocks will be significantly warmer than lighter ones, and can deter animals that do not have a high tolerance for heat.<ref name=\"Brusca\"/>\nThe northern Gulf of California experiences tidal ranges of up to {{convert|5|m|abbr=on}}. Mixed [[semidiurnal tides]] are the norm throughout most of the Gulf.\n\n;Estuaries\nIn the Gulf of California, there are a number of negative [[estuary|estuaries]], that is, ones in which the [[evaporation]] of seawater is relatively greater than that of the fresh water input. The salinities of these inlets are higher than that of the [[ocean]]. The temperatures, [[Poikilotherm#Ecological niches|poikilothermal]], of these negative [[estuary|estuaries]] also are higher than the general temperature of the Gulf.\n\nIt is possible that at one time these estuaries were positive, that is, ones in which the [[seawater]] component is [[Concentration|diluted]]; therefore, the water is [[brackish water|brackish]], with salinity less than that of the ocean.\n\nHowever, due to human settlement around the Gulf of California and water diversion for municipal and agricultural use in an area of comparatively low rainfall, there are no longer many rivers that freely empty into the Gulf of California. The upper [[Colorado River Delta]] is one example of a historically major estuary and [[wetlands]] [[ecosystem]], that since the 20th century construction of upriver dams and diversion aqueducts on the [[Colorado River]], is now a small [[ephemeral]] remnant estuary. The remaining Gulf inlets still are important to several species of fishes, [[crustacean]]s, and [[shellfish]] that are commercially harvested.<ref name=\"Brusca\"/>\n\n==History==\n\n==Climate==\n;Air\nEven though the shores of the Gulf of California are generally sheltered from the continuous wave shock that is experienced by most other North American shores, storms known as a \"[[chubasco]]\" can cause significant damage to shorelines, despite their brevity.<ref name=\"Brusca\"/>\n\n;Ocean\nThe depth of the water helps to determine its temperature. For example, shallow depths are directly influenced by the local temperature of the air, while deeper waters are less susceptible to changes in air temperature.<ref name=\"Brusca\"/> The temperature of the water in the Gulf of California generally experiences lows of {{convert|16|\u00b0C|abbr=on}} in winter and highs of {{convert|24|\u00b0C|abbr=on}} in summer. But temperatures can vary greatly in the gulf, and the water is almost always warmer by the coast than the open ocean. For example, the waters surrounding La Paz reach {{convert|30|\u00b0C|abbr=on}} in August, while the waters in neighboring city Cabo San Lucas, only reach {{convert|26|\u00b0C|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Nix\"/><ref name=\"deepmexico.com\">[http://www.deepmexico.com/es/ocean_dives.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111221075834/http://www.deepmexico.com/es/ocean_dives.html |date=December 21, 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"redalyc.uaemex.mx\">{{cite web |url=http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/html/479/47942204/47942204.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-06-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120715160509/http://redalyc.uaemex.mx/redalyc/html/479/47942204/47942204.html |archivedate=2012-07-15 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://math.ucr.edu/ftm/bajaPages/MarineBiology.html |title=Marine Biology of Baja California |publisher=Math.ucr.edu |date= |accessdate=2013-12-08}}</ref>\n\nOccasionally, the northern Gulf of California will go through significantly cold winters. The water in the Northern Gulf can sometimes drop below {{convert|8|\u00b0C|abbr=on}}, which can lead to a large die-off of marine organisms. The animals most susceptible to the large decrease in water temperature include macroscopic algae and plankton.<ref name=\"Brusca\"/>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Average sea temperatures of [[Puerto Pe\u00f1asco]]<ref name=\"redalyc.uaemex.mx\"/>\n|-\n!'''Jan'''\n!'''Feb'''\n!'''Mar'''\n!'''Apr'''\n!'''May'''\n!'''Jun'''\n!'''Jul'''\n!'''Aug'''\n!'''Sep'''\n!'''Oct'''\n!'''Nov'''\n!'''Dec'''\n|-\n|17&nbsp;\u00b0C\n63&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|16&nbsp;\u00b0C\n61&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|17&nbsp;\u00b0C\n63&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|19&nbsp;\u00b0C\n66&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|21&nbsp;\u00b0C\n70&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|23&nbsp;\u00b0C\n73&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|26&nbsp;\u00b0C\n79&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|28&nbsp;\u00b0C\n82&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|28&nbsp;\u00b0C\n82&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|26&nbsp;\u00b0C\n79&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|23&nbsp;\u00b0C\n73&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|19&nbsp;\u00b0C\n66&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Average sea temperatures of [[La Paz, Baja California Sur|La Paz]]<ref name=\"deepmexico.com\"/>\n|-\n!'''Jan'''\n!'''Feb'''\n!'''Mar'''\n!'''Apr'''\n!'''May'''\n!'''Jun'''\n!'''Jul'''\n!'''Aug'''\n!'''Sep'''\n!'''Oct'''\n!'''Nov'''\n!'''Dec'''\n|-\n|19&nbsp;\u00b0C\n66&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|19&nbsp;\u00b0C\n66&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|21&nbsp;\u00b0C\n70&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|23&nbsp;\u00b0C\n73&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|25&nbsp;\u00b0C\n77&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|27&nbsp;\u00b0C\n81&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|28&nbsp;\u00b0C\n82&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|30&nbsp;\u00b0C\n85&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|28&nbsp;\u00b0C\n82&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|27&nbsp;\u00b0C\n81&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|24&nbsp;\u00b0C\n75&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|21&nbsp;\u00b0C\n70&nbsp;\u00b0F\n\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Average sea temperatures of [[Cabo San Lucas]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.surf-forecast.com/breaks/San-Jorge/seatemp |title=San Jorge Water Temperature (Sea) and Wetsuit Guide (Baja Sur, Mexico) |publisher=Surf-forecast.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-08}}</ref>\n|-\n!'''Jan'''\n!'''Feb'''\n!'''Mar'''\n!'''Apr'''\n!'''May'''\n!'''Jun'''\n!'''Jul'''\n!'''Aug'''\n!'''Sep'''\n!'''Oct'''\n!'''Nov'''\n!'''Dec'''\n|-\n|20&nbsp;\u00b0C\n68&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|19&nbsp;\u00b0C\n66&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|19&nbsp;\u00b0C\n66&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|19&nbsp;\u00b0C\n66&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|20&nbsp;\u00b0C\n68&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|21&nbsp;\u00b0C\n70&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|24&nbsp;\u00b0C\n75&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|26&nbsp;\u00b0C\n79&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|26&nbsp;\u00b0C\n79&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|26&nbsp;\u00b0C\n79&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|24&nbsp;\u00b0C\n75&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|22&nbsp;\u00b0C\n72&nbsp;\u00b0F\n|}\n\n==Marine life==\n[[File:Giant pacific manta.jpg|left|frame|Giant Pacific [[manta ray]]]]\nThe narrow sea is home to a rich ecosystem. In addition to a wide range of [[endemic (ecology)|endemic]] creatures, such as the critically endangered [[vaquita]], it hosts many migratory species, such as the [[humpback whale]], [[California gray whale]], [[killer whale]], [[manta ray]], [[Humboldt squid]] and [[leatherback sea turtle]], and the world's largest animal, the [[blue whale]]. The unusual resident populations of [[fin whale]]s and [[sperm whale]]s do not migrate annually. The area near the delta of the Colorado river has a small remnant population of the [[totoaba]] fish. This region has historically been a magnet for world-class sport [[fishing]] activities, with a rich history of sporting world records.\n\nThe region also has a rich history as a commercial [[fishery]]. However, the data vary wildly according to the species being studied, and the Gulf's ability to recuperate after years of overfishing remains uncertain. Moreover, changes in terrestrial ecology, such as the vast reduction in flow from the Colorado River into the Gulf, have negatively affected fisheries, particularly in the northern region.\n\nThe Gulf of California sustains a large number of marine mammals, many of which are rare and endangered. Its more than 900 islands are important nesting sites for thousands of seabirds, and its waters are primary breeding, feeding, and nursing grounds for myriad migratory and resident fish species. For decades, the gulf has been a primary source of two of Mexico's leading marine resources, sardines and anchovies. Water pollution is a problem in the Gulf of California, but the more immediate concerns are overfishing and bottom trawling, which destroys eelgrass beds and shellfish.\n\nEfforts by the Mexican government to create [[Conservation ethic|conservation zones]] and [[nature reserve]]s have been hampered by lack of enforcement resources, as well as a lack of a political consensus on this issue of conservation of the Gulf.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}} This occurs even though significant areas are a [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]]. The thousands of miles of coastline are remote and difficult to police, and the politically powerful commercial fishing industry has been slow to embrace even economically viable conservation measures, much less strict measures of conservation. Conservation of the Gulf's fisheries and coastlines is also complicated by a long history of overcapitalization in the sector, and the direct, often negative, impacts that conservation measures have on the livelihoods of Mexico's coastal inhabitants. At present, the Mexican government and business interests have promoted a macro-level, tourist development vision for the Gulf, the impacts of which on local ecology and society are uncertain. In 2019, the gulf was added to the [[List of World Heritage in Danger]] because of concerns of the imminent extinction of the [[vaquita]], an endemic porpoise in the area.<ref name=\"whs danger\">{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/news/1999 |title=The Islands and Protected Areas of the Gulf of California (Mexico) inscribed on the List of World Heritage in Danger |publisher=UNESCO |accessdate=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nCoastal communities are highly reliant on both commercial and sport fishing, including [[San Felipe, Baja California|San Felipe]], [[San Carlos, Sonora]], [[Cabo San Lucas]], [[La Paz, Baja California Sur|La Paz]], [[Loreto, Baja California Sur|Loreto]], [[Guaymas]], [[Bah\u00eda Kino]], [[Puerto Pe\u00f1asco]], [[Topolobampo]] and [[Muleg\u00e9]]. The well-developed shrimp and sardine fleets of [[Mazatl\u00e1n]], on the Mexican mainland's Pacific coast, heavily exploit the commercial fisheries of the southern Gulf.\n\nMany marine organisms can only survive within a particular [[salinity]] range, which makes salinity a notable factor in determining the types of potentially commercial organisms found in the Gulf of California. The mean annual ranges of salinity of the Sea of Cortez are between 3.5 and 3.58% at the surface.<ref name=\"Nix\"/> Furthermore, the salinity of the water of the Northern Gulf of California is generally higher than the Central and Southern faunal regions due to the increased amount of evaporation that occurs in that region.<ref name=\"Brusca\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of western shore communities on the Gulf of California]]\n* [[List of eastern shore communities on the Gulf of California]] \n* [[Ferdinand Kon\u0161\u010dak]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|author=Brusca, Richard C. (Editor)|title=The Gulf of California: Biodiversity and Conservation|publisher=University of Arizona Press|date= 2010|pages=354 pages}} Studies by researchers, on both sides of the border, on the threats to the diversity of species in the gulf's waters.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikisource}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20151103082949/http://cedointercultural.org/ CEDO Intercultural]\n* [http://www.desertmuseum.org/center/seaofcortez/ Desert Museum]\n* [http://bajaex.com/protect-wild-baja/ Friends of Wild Baja conserves and protects the critical habitats and biodiversity of The Gulf of California]\n \n{{List of seas}}\n{{coastal geography}}\n{{World Heritage Sites in M\u00e9xico}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gulf Of California}}\n[[Category:Gulf of California| ]]\n[[Category:Gulfs of Mexico|California]]\n[[Category:Gulfs of the Pacific Ocean|California, Gulf of]]\n[[Category:Pacific Coast of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Baja California]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Baja California Sur]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Sonora]]\n[[Category:Landforms of Sinaloa]]\n[[Category:Colorado River]]\n[[Category:Ecoregions of Mexico]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Cenozoic Mexico]]\n[[Category:Cenozoic rifts and grabens]]\n", "name_user": "G\u0142odny", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed incorrect information (Baja California is not the second longest Peninsula of the world)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gulf_of_California"}
{"title_page": "Indian robin", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Indian robin\n| image = Indian robin (Saxicoloides fulicatus cambaiensis) male.jpg\n| image_caption = Male of race ''cambaiensis''<br>[[Kanha National Park]], [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| image2 = Indian robin (Saxicoloides fulicatus cambaiensis) female Narlai.jpg\n| image2_caption = Female of race ''cambaiensis'' ([[Rajasthan]])\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22710023/0 |title=''Saxicoloides fulicatus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Copsychus\n| species = fulicatus\n| authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], 1766)\n| synonyms = *''Motacilla fulicata'' {{small|Linnaeus,&nbsp;1766}}<ref>{{cite book|author=Linnaeus|year=1766|title=Systema Naturae i:336 (Ceylon)}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Baker, E C Stuart|year=1921|title=A hand-list of genera and species of birds of the Indian Empire|journal=Jour. Bom. Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=27|issue=1|pages=87|url=https://archive.org/details/handlistofgenera00bake}}</ref>\n*''Saxicoloides fulicata'' {{small|(Linnaeus,&nbsp;1766)}}\n*''Sylvia cambaiensis'' {{small|(Latham,&nbsp;1790)}}\n*''Thamnobia cambaiensis'' {{small|(Latham,&nbsp;1790)}}\n*''Thamnobia fulicata'' {{small|(Linnaeus,&nbsp;1766)}}\n*''Sylvia ptymatura''<ref>{{cite book|title=Catalogue of the Genera and Subgenera of Birds Contained in the British Museum|publisher=British Museum Natural History|author=George Robert Gray|year=1855|pages=36}}</ref>\n| range_map = SaxicoloidesFulicatusMap.svg\n}}\nThe '''Indian robin''' (''Copsychus fulicatus''<ref group=note>Rasmussen & Anderton emend the species epithet from ''fulicata'' to ''fulicatus'' since ''Saxicola'' is masculine and the ''-oides'' ending is always masculine according to ICZN Code 30.1.4.4. [http://www.iczn.org/iczn/index.jsp?nfv=true&article=30 ICZN Code] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924033134/http://www.iczn.org/iczn/index.jsp?nfv=true&article=30 |date=2015-09-24 }}. See also {{cite journal|last=David|first=Normand|last2=Gosselin|first2=Michel |year=2002|title=The grammatical gender of avian genera|journal=Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club |volume=122|issue=4|pages=257\u2013282|url= https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40416636}}</ref>) is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Muscicapidae]].\nIt is widespread in the [[Indian subcontinent]], and ranges across [[Bangladesh]], [[Bhutan]], [[India]], [[Nepal]], [[Pakistan]], and [[Sri Lanka]]. The males of northern populations have a brown back whose extent gradually reduces southwards with populations in the southern peninsula having an all black back. They are commonly found in open scrub areas and often seen running along the ground or perching on low thorny shrubs and rocks. The long tail is usually held up and the chestnut undertail coverts and dark body make them easily distinguishable from [[pied bushchat]]s and [[oriental magpie robin]]s.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nIn 1760 the French zoologist [[Mathurin Jacques Brisson]] included a description of the Indian robin in his ''Ornithologie'' based on a specimen that he mistakenly  believed had been collected in the Philippines. He used the French name ''Le grand traquet des Philippines'' and the Latin ''Rubetra Philippensis Major''.<ref name=brisson>{{ cite book | last=Brisson | first=Mathurin Jacques | author-link=Mathurin Jacques Brisson | year=1760 | title=Ornithologie, ou, M\u00e9thode contenant la division des oiseaux en ordres, sections, genres, especes & leurs vari\u00e9t\u00e9s | volume=Volume 3 | language=French, Latin | place=Paris | publisher=Jean-Baptiste Bauche | pages=444\u2013446, Plate 23 fig 2 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/35953503 }} The two stars (**) at the start of the section indicates that Brisson based his description on the examination of a specimen.</ref> Although Brisson coined Latin names, these do not conform to the [[binomial nomenclature|binomial system]] and are not recognised by the [[International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature]].<ref name=allen>{{cite journal |last=Allen | first=J.A. | author-link=Joel Asaph Allen | year=1910 | title=Collation of Brisson's genera of birds with those of Linnaeus |journal=Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History |volume=28 | pages=317\u2013335 | hdl=2246/678 }}</ref> When in 1766 the Swedish naturalist [[Carl Linnaeus]] updated his ''[[Systema Naturae]]'' for the [[12th edition of Systema Naturae|twelfth edition]], he added 240 species that had been previously described by Brisson.<ref name=allen/> One of these was the Indian robin. Linnaeus included a brief description, coined the [[binomial name]] ''Motacilla fulicata'' and cited Brisson's work.<ref>{{cite book | last=Linnaeus | first=Carl | authorlink=Carl Linnaeus | year=1766 | title=Systema naturae : per regna tria natura, secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis | edition=12th | volume=Volume 1, Part 1 | publisher=Laurentii Salvii  | place=Holmiae (Stockholm) | language=Latin | page=336 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/42946532 }}</ref> The [[type location (biology)|type location]] was subsequently corrected to [[Puducherry]] in southern India.<ref>{{ cite book | editor1-last=Mayr | editor1-first=Ernst | editor1-link=Ernst Mayr | editor2-last=Paynter | editor2-first=Raymond A. Jr | year=1964 | title=Check-list of Birds of the World | volume=Volume 10 | publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology  | place=Cambridge, Massachusetts  | pages=133\u2013134 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14486322 }}</ref> The [[Specific name (zoology)|specific name]] is from the Latin ''fulicatus'' for \"dusky\" or \"black\".<ref name=hbwkey>{{cite web | last=Jobling | first=J.A. | year=2018 | title= Key to Scientific Names in Ornithology | editor1-last=del Hoyo | editor1-first=J. | editor2-last=Elliott | editor2-first=A. | editor3-last=Sargatal | editor3-first=J. | editor4-last=Christie | editor4-first=D.A. | editor5-last=de Juana | editor5-first=E. | website=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive | publisher=Lynx Edicions | url=https://www.hbw.com/dictionary/definition/fulicata-fulicatus | accessdate=10 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe Indian robin was formerly placed in the [[monotypic]] genus ''Saxicoloides''. It was moved to ''[[Copsychus]]'' based on the results of [[molecular phylogenetic]] studies of birds in the family [[Muscicapidae]].<ref>{{ cite journal | last1=Sangster  | first1=G. | last2=Alstr\u00f6m | first2=P. | last3=Forsmark | first3=E. | last4=Olsson | first4=U. | year=2010 | title=Multi-locus phylogenetic analysis of Old World chats and flycatchers reveals extensive paraphyly at family, subfamily and genus level (Aves: Muscicapidae) | journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume=57 | issue=1 | pages=380\u2013392 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2010.07.008 | pmid=20656044}}</ref><ref>{{ cite journal | last1=Zuccon | first1=D. | last2=Ericson | first2=P.G.P. | year=2010 | title=A multi-gene phylogeny disentangles the chat-flycatcher complex (Aves: Muscicapidae) | journal=Zoologica Scripta  | volume=39 | issue=3 | pages=213\u2013224 | doi=10.1111/j.1463-6409.2010.00423.x }}</ref><ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | title=Chats, Old World flycatchers | website=World Bird List Version 6.2 | url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/chats/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union| accessdate=20 May 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Voelker|first=Gary|last2=Pe\u00f1alba|first2=Joshua V.|last3=Huntley|first3=Jerry W.|last4=Bowie|first4=Rauri C. K.|date=2014-04-01|title=Diversification in an Afro-Asian songbird clade (Erythropygia\u2013Copsychus) reveals founder-event speciation via trans-oceanic dispersals and a southern to northern colonization pattern in Africa|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution |volume=73|pages=97\u2013105|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2014.01.024|pmid=24508703}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Indian Robin (Saxicoloides fulicata) in Kawal, AP W IMG 2031.jpg|thumb|left|Male from Andhra Pradesh, showing features of ''intermedius'']]\nThe Indian robin is sexually dimorphic in plumage with the male being mainly black with a white shoulder patch or stripe whose visible extent can vary with posture. The northern populations have the upper plumage brownish while the southern populations are black above. The males have chestnut undertail coverts and these are visible as the bird usually holds the 6\u20138&nbsp;cm long tail raised upright. The females are brownish above, have no white shoulder stripe and are greyish below with the vent a paler shade of chestnut than the males. Birds of the northern populations are larger than those from southern India or Sri Lanka. Juvenile birds are much like females but the throat is mottled.<ref name=ras/>\n\nSeveral populations are named based on their plumage differences. The nominate subspecies refers to the population found across southern Peninsular India. Race ''leucopterus'' is found in [[Sri Lanka]]. Race ''cambaiensis'' of western India and ''erythrura''  (=''erythrurus'') of eastern India (south to around Sambalpur<ref>{{cite journal|author=Majumdar, N |year=1980| title= Occurrence of the Bengal Black Robin, ''Saxicoloides fulicata erythrura'' (Lesson) [Muscicapidae: Turdinae], and the Assam Purple Sunbird, ''Nectarinia asiatica intermedia'' (Hume) [Nectariniidae] in Orissa State| journal= J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc. |volume=77|issue=2|page=334|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/44708256}}</ref>) have the males with brown backs. The population ''intermedius'' includes forms between ''cambaiensis'', ''erythrura'' and ''fulicata'' in central India and parts of the Deccan region. A race ''munda'' was named on the basis of a specimen from Punjab but is now considered synonymous with ''cambaiensis''.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Van Tyne, J.  |author2=W. Koelz|year=1936|title=Seven new birds from the Punjab|journal=Occ. Pap. Mus. Zool. Univ. Michigan|volume=334|pages=5}}</ref> Older classifications treat the population in southern India under the name ''ptymatura'' while considering the type locality as Sri Lanka<ref name=whistler>{{cite book|title=Popular Handbook of Indian Birds|edition= 3rd|author=Hugh Whistler|year=1941|publisher=Gurney and Jackson|pages=104\u2013106|url=https://archive.org/stream/popularhandbooko033226mbp#page/n141/mode/2up}}</ref> although the type locality has subsequently been restricted to Pondicherry.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Ripley, SD|url=http://www.peabody.yale.edu/scipubs/bulletins_postillas/ypmP013_1952.pdf|year=1952|journal=Postilla|volume=13|title=The Thrushes|pages=1\u201348|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100627030143/http://www.peabody.yale.edu/scipubs/bulletins_postillas/ypmP013_1952.pdf|archivedate=2010-06-27}}</ref>\n\nLocal names recorded by [[Thomas C. Jerdon|Jerdon]] include ''Nalanchi'' (Telugu), ''Wannatikuruvi'' (Tamil, ''Washerman bird''), ''Kalchuri'' (Hindi) and ''Paan kiriththaa'' (Sinhala).<ref>{{cite book|title=The Birds of India. Volume 2 (part 1)|author=Jerdon, T. C.|year=1863|publisher=Military Orphan Press, Calcutta|pages=[https://archive.org/details/birdsofindiabein21jerd/page/121 121]|url=https://archive.org/details/birdsofindiabein21jerd}}</ref> The genus name indicates that it looks similar to ''Saxicola'', the genus of the [[pied bushchat]], a bird often found in similar habitats.\n[[File:Thar Bird.jpg|alt=Male fulicatus from Tharparkar, Sindh|left|thumb|Male from [[Tharparkar]], Sindh, Pakistan]]\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThis bird is found in open stony, grassy and scrub forest habitats. They are mainly found in dry habitats and are mostly absent from the thicker forest regions and high rainfall areas. All populations are resident and non-migratory. The species is often found close to human habitation and will frequently perch on rooftops.<ref name=ras>{{cite book|year=2005|title=Birds of South Asia: The Ripley Guide. Volume 2|page=396|publisher= Smithsonian Institution and Lynx Edicions|author1=Rasmussen PC  |author2=Anderton, JC }}</ref><ref name=whistler/>\n\nThe species was introduced into the New York region but did not establish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fws.gov/migratorybirds/issues/nonnative/Final%20NonNative%20Species%20List.pdf|title=Notices - Federal Register - March 15, 2005 Vol. 70, No. 49|author=USFWS|publisher=US Fish and Wildlife Service|date=2005-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Bull, J.|year=1974|title=Birds of New York state|publisher=American Museum of Natural History, New York}}</ref> A vagrant or escape has been noted from the Maldives.<ref name=ras/>\n\n==Ecology==\nPopulation densities of 193-240 individuals per square km have been estimated in the Pondicherry University campus. The ratio of males to females was about 1.5:1. Territory size for males is estimated at about 6650 m<sup>2</sup>.<ref>{{cite book|author=Rajasekhar, B|year=1993|chapter=Use of line transects to estimate Indian Robin (''Saxicoloides fulicata'') population at Pondicherry University Campus|title=Bird Conservation: Strategies for the Nineties and Beyond|editor=Verghese, A|editor2=Sridhar, S|editor3=Chakravarthy, AK| publisher=Ornithological Society of India, Bangalore|pages=191| chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/BirdConservationStrategies/BirdConservationIndia#page/n217/mode/1up}}.</ref> Males can be aggressive to others during the breeding season and will even attack reflections.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Wikramanayake, EB|year=1952|title=Blackbacked Robin attacking car|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=50|issue=3|page=656|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48057259}}</ref> Human activities such as felling and firewood removal in forests appear to benefit them.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Conservation and Society|pages=562\u2013591|volume=4|issue=4|year=2006|title=Consequences of Rural Biomass Extraction for Bird Communities in an Indian Tropical Dry Forest and the Role of Vegetation Structure|author1=Kumar, Raman|author2=Shahabuddin, Ghazala|url=http://www.conservationandsociety.org/cs_4_4_4-562.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070821082742/http://www.conservationandsociety.org/cs_4_4_4-562.pdf|archivedate=2007-08-21}}</ref>\n\n===Food===\nThey feed mostly on insects but are known to take frogs and lizards especially when feeding young at the nest.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Sivasubramanian, C|year=1991|title=Frog and lizard in the dietary of the Indian Robin ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' (Linn.)|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=88|issue=3|page=458|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48673894}}</ref> Individuals may forage late in the evening to capture insects attracted to lights.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Bharos, A. M. K.|year=1997|title=Indian Robin ''Saxicola fulicata'' foraging in the light of fluorescent lamps|journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society|volume=94|page=571|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48601949}}</ref>\n\n===Breeding===\n[[File:Indian Robin bird (Saxicoloides fulicatus) Nest and Eggs 01.JPG|thumb|right|Nest with eggs.]]\nThe breeding season is December to September but varies according to region and usually begins with the first rains.<ref name=betts/> Peak breeding in northern India is in June<ref name=oates/> and is earlier in Southern India.<ref name=betts/> In Sri Lanka it breeds in March to June and August to September.<ref name=ras/> Males sing during this season and display by lowering and spreading their tail feathers and strutting around the female, displaying their sides and fluffing their undertail coverts.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Thyagaraju, A. S.|year=1955|title=The courtship (?) display of the Blackbacked Indian Robin [''Saxicoloides fulicata'' (Linn.)]|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc. |volume=53|issue=1|pages=129\u2013130|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48180511}}</ref> The songs of males have variants for inviting mates and for deterring other males.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Breeding biology of Indian Robin ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' in northern India|author=Kumar, A|url= http://connectjournals.com/file_full_text/1300001H_7.pdf| year=2012| journal=J. Exp. Zool. India|volume=15| issue=1|pages=57\u201361}}</ref> Males will drive away other males and patrol their territory by flying with slow wing-beats from perch to perch. They may sometimes peck at their reflections.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Wikramanayake, E.B.|year=1952|title=Blackbacked robin [''Saxicoloides f. fulicata'' (Linn.)] attacking car|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=50|issue=3|page=656|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48057259}}</ref> An aggressive display involves fluffing up the feathers and holding the bill high.<ref name=hbk/>\n[[File:Indian Robin (Saxicoloides fulicata)- Male with feed for Immature W IMG 8064.jpg|thumb|left|Male feeding young ([[Parli, Maharashtra|Parli]], [[India]]).]]\nNests are built between rocks, in holes in walls or in a tree hollow.<ref>{{cite journal|year=1996|title=Peculiar nesting site and some observations on the breeding behaviour of Indian Robin ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' Linn|journal=[[Newsletter for Birdwatchers]] |volume=36|issue=1|pages=3\u20135|author1=Shanbhag, AB|author2=Gramopadhye, A|url=https://archive.org/stream/NLBW36_1#page/n1/mode/1up}}</ref> Nests are lined with animal hair and it has been noted that many nests have pieces of snake sloughs.<ref name=whistler/><ref>{{cite journal|journal=The Auk|volume = 43|issue= 4|year=1926| title= On the use, by birds, of snakes' sloughs as nesting material|author=Strecker, John K|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v043n04/p0501-p0507.pdf|pages=501\u2013507|doi=10.2307/4075138|jstor = 4075138}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://archive.org/stream/ibisns03brit#page/430/mode/2up/ | title=Notes on various Indian birds|author=Beavan, RC| authorlink=Robert Cecil Beavan|journal=Ibis| volume=3 | pages=430\u2013455|year=1867|issue=12|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1867.tb06443.x}}</ref> The eggs are of regular oval form, but many are elongated and a few pointed. They have a fair amount of gloss. The ground-colour is white, often tinged with faint green or pink, and this is rather closely spotted, speckled, streaked, and mottled, with rich reddish or umber-brown and brownish yellow, with some underlying lavender. The markings are denser at the larger end of the egg, where they form an irregular cap. Some eggs are blotched with dark reddish brown at the large end. Eggs are about {{convert|0.76|-|0.84|in|cm}} long and {{convert|0.55|-|0.62|in|cm}} wide.<ref name=oates>{{cite book|author=Oates, E W|year=1905 |title=Catalogue of the collection of birds' eggs in the British Museum |volume=4|pages=151\u2013153 |url=https://archive.org/stream/catalogueofcolle04brit#page/150/mode/2up}}</ref> Three to four eggs is the usual clutch.<ref>{{cite book|author=Oates, E. W. 1890|title=The Fauna of British India, Including Ceylon and Burma. Birds. Volume 2|date=1889-98|publisher=Taylor and Francis London| pages=[https://archive.org/details/birdsindia02oaterich/page/115 115]|url=https://archive.org/details/birdsindia02oaterich }}</ref> An abnormal clutch of seven has been noted although none of the eggs hatched at this nest.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Javed|first=Salim|year=1990|title=Abnormal clutch in Indian Brownbacked Robin ''Saxicoloides fulicata cambaiensis'' (Latham)|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=89|issue=2|page=258|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48732722}}</ref> Only the female incubates.<ref>{{cite book|author=Ali, S|year=1997|title=The Book of Indian Birds|edition=12th|isbn=978-0-19-563731-1|publisher=Oxford University Press|oclc=214935260}}</ref> Eggs hatch in about 10\u201312 days.<ref name=hbk>{{cite book|author1=Ali, S  |author2=S Dillon Ripley|pages=61\u201367|title=Handbook of the birds of India and Pakistan|volume=9|edition=2nd|year=1998|publisher=Oxford University Press}}</ref> Chicks have black down.<ref name=betts>{{cite journal|author=Betts, F N |year=1951| title=The birds of Coorg. Part 1 |journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc. |volume=50|issue=1|pages=20\u201363|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48056474}}</ref> Both males and females feed the young, the males sometimes passing food to the female which in turn feeds the young.<ref name=hbk/><ref>{{cite journal|author=George, JC |year=1961|title=Parental cooperation in the feeding of nestlings in the Indian Robin|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=58|issue=1|pages=267\u2013268|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/47540817}}</ref> Nestlings may feign dead ([[thanatosis]]) when handled.<ref name=hbk/> Nestlings may be preyed on by the [[rufous treepie]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Begbie, A|year=1905|title=Nest of the Brown-backed Indian Robin ''Thamnobia cambaiensis''|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=16|issue=3|page=513|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/5725855}}</ref> The same nest site may be reused in subsequent years.<ref name=hbk/><ref>{{cite journal|author= Naik, RM |year=1963| title= On the nesting habits of the Indian Robin, ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' (Linnaeus)|journal=[[Newsletter for Birdwatchers]] |volume=3| issue=9|page=7|url=https://archive.org/stream/NLBW3#page/n139/mode/1up}}</ref>\n\nAn old anecdotal record of these birds laying their eggs in the nests of ''[[Turdoides]]'' babblers has not been supported by later observers.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Field, F|year=1902|title=Robin laying in babbler's nest|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=14|issue=3|pages=610\u2013611|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/30158289}}</ref> Laboratory studies have demonstrated cyclic changes in the [[melanin]] pigmentation of the tissue surrounding the testes. The dark pigmentation is lost during the breeding season and regained later.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Poult. Sci.|year=1983|volume=62|issue=2|pages=385\u2013388|title=Instance of melanosis in the gonads of male Indian Robin, ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' (Lin)|vauthors=Agrawal SC, Bansal G |pmid=6835913|doi=10.3382/ps.0620385|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n===Parasites===\nSeveral parasites including a [[cestode]] have been identified in this species.<ref>{{cite journal|title=A new avian cestode from ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' at Aurangabad (M.S.) India|vauthors=Shinde GB, Gharge MD, Gavhane AB, Jadhav BV |journal=[[Rivista di Parassitologia]]|year=1990|volume=51|issue=3|pages=255\u2013257}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=''Haemaphysalis kutchensis'' sp. n., a Common Larval and Nymphal Parasite of Birds in Northwestern India (Ixodoidea, Ixodidae)|author1=Harry Hoogstraal |author2=Harold Trapido |journal=The Journal of Parasitology|volume=49|issue=3|date=1 June 1963|pages=489\u2013497|doi=10.2307/3275824|issn=0022-3395|jstor=3275824}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==Other sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n* George, JC (1963) Some observations on the breeding behaviour of the Indian Robin, ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' (Linnaeus). Pavo 1(2):71-78.\n* Magon, VK (1979) Distribution of acid phosphatase in the digestive system of two Indian birds, ''Uroloncha malabarica'' and ''Saxicoloides fulicata''. Pavo 17(1&2):27-32.\n* Rajvanshi, G; Gupta, MM; Yeshowardhana; Singh, VS. (1985) Histochemical localization of calcium and iron in the gonad of male Indian Robin (''Saxicoloides fulicata''). Pavo 23(1&2):31-36.\n* Rajvanshi, G; Gupta, MM; Bhatnagar, VK; Bhatnagar, Sumar (1985) Cyclic changes in Carbohydrate localization in gonad of male Indian Robin ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' (Linn.). Pavo 23(1&2):41-46.\n* Gupta, MM; Rajvanshi, G; Singh, VS. (1986) Histochemical localization of proteins and Tryptophane aminoacid in testis of Indian Robin ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' (Linn.). Pavo 24(1&2):69-76.\n* {{cite journal|author=Culshaw, JC|year=1948|title=Some observations on the territories of Blackbacked Indian Robins ''Saxicoloides fulicata fulicata'', Linn|journal=Jour. Bengal Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=22|issue=3|pages=92}}\n*{{cite journal|author=Stonor, CR|year=1944|title= On the display of the Indian Robin, ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' (Linnaeus)|journal=Ibis|volume=86|issue=1|pages=91\u201393|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1944.tb07534.x}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Copsychus fulicatus}}\n* [http://ibc.lynxeds.com/species/indian-robin-saxicoloides-fulicatus Internet Bird Collection]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1591245|from2=Q27075634}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:robin, Indian}}\n[[Category:Copsychus|Indian robin]]\n[[Category:Robins|Indian robin]]\n[[Category:Birds of India]]\n[[Category:Birds of South Asia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1766|Indian robin]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Indian robin\n| image = Indian robin (Saxicoloides fulicatus cambaiensis) male.jpg\n| image_caption = Male of race ''cambaiensis''<br>[[Kanha National Park]], [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| image2 = Indian robin (Saxicoloides fulicatus cambaiensis) female Narlai.jpg\n| image2_caption = Female of race ''cambaiensis'' ([[Rajasthan]])\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22710023/0 |title=''Saxicoloides fulicatus'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Copsychus\n| species = fulicatus\n| authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], 1766)\n| synonyms = *''Motacilla fulicata'' {{small|Linnaeus,&nbsp;1766}}<ref>{{cite book|author=Linnaeus|year=1766|title=Systema Naturae i:336 (Ceylon)}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Baker, E C Stuart|year=1921|title=A hand-list of genera and species of birds of the Indian Empire|journal=Jour. Bom. Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=27|issue=1|pages=87|url=https://archive.org/details/handlistofgenera00bake}}</ref>\n*''Saxicoloides fulicata'' {{small|(Linnaeus,&nbsp;1766)}}\n*''Sylvia cambaiensis'' {{small|(Latham,&nbsp;1790)}}\n*''Thamnobia cambaiensis'' {{small|(Latham,&nbsp;1790)}}\n*''Thamnobia fulicata'' {{small|(Linnaeus,&nbsp;1766)}}\n*''Sylvia ptymatura''<ref>{{cite book|title=Catalogue of the Genera and Subgenera of Birds Contained in the British Museum|publisher=British Museum Natural History|author=George Robert Gray|year=1855|pages=36}}</ref>\n| range_map = SaxicoloidesFulicatusMap.svg\n}}\nThe '''Indian robin''' (''Copsychus fulicatus''<ref group=note>Rasmussen & Anderton emend the species epithet from ''fulicata'' to ''fulicatus'' since ''Saxicola'' is masculine and the ''-oides'' ending is always masculine according to ICZN Code 30.1.4.4. [http://www.iczn.org/iczn/index.jsp?nfv=true&article=30 ICZN Code] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924033134/http://www.iczn.org/iczn/index.jsp?nfv=true&article=30 |date=2015-09-24 }}. See also {{cite journal|last=David|first=Normand|last2=Gosselin|first2=Michel |year=2002|title=The grammatical gender of avian genera|journal=Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club |volume=122|issue=4|pages=257\u2013282}}</ref>) is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Muscicapidae]].\nIt is widespread in the [[Indian subcontinent]], and ranges across [[Bangladesh]], [[Bhutan]], [[India]], [[Nepal]], [[Pakistan]], and [[Sri Lanka]]. The males of northern populations have a brown back whose extent gradually reduces southwards with populations in the southern peninsula having an all black back. They are commonly found in open scrub areas and often seen running along the ground or perching on low thorny shrubs and rocks. The long tail is usually held up and the chestnut undertail coverts and dark body make them easily distinguishable from [[pied bushchat]]s and [[oriental magpie robin]]s.\n\n==Taxonomy==\nIn 1760 the French zoologist [[Mathurin Jacques Brisson]] included a description of the Indian robin in his ''Ornithologie'' based on a specimen that he mistakenly  believed had been collected in the Philippines. He used the French name ''Le grand traquet des Philippines'' and the Latin ''Rubetra Philippensis Major''.<ref name=brisson>{{ cite book | last=Brisson | first=Mathurin Jacques | author-link=Mathurin Jacques Brisson | year=1760 | title=Ornithologie, ou, M\u00e9thode contenant la division des oiseaux en ordres, sections, genres, especes & leurs vari\u00e9t\u00e9s | volume=Volume 3 | language=French, Latin | place=Paris | publisher=Jean-Baptiste Bauche | pages=444\u2013446, Plate 23 fig 2 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/35953503 }} The two stars (**) at the start of the section indicates that Brisson based his description on the examination of a specimen.</ref> Although Brisson coined Latin names, these do not conform to the [[binomial nomenclature|binomial system]] and are not recognised by the [[International Commission on Zoological Nomenclature]].<ref name=allen>{{cite journal |last=Allen | first=J.A. | author-link=Joel Asaph Allen | year=1910 | title=Collation of Brisson's genera of birds with those of Linnaeus |journal=Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History |volume=28 | pages=317\u2013335 | hdl=2246/678 }}</ref> When in 1766 the Swedish naturalist [[Carl Linnaeus]] updated his ''[[Systema Naturae]]'' for the [[12th edition of Systema Naturae|twelfth edition]], he added 240 species that had been previously described by Brisson.<ref name=allen/> One of these was the Indian robin. Linnaeus included a brief description, coined the [[binomial name]] ''Motacilla fulicata'' and cited Brisson's work.<ref>{{cite book | last=Linnaeus | first=Carl | authorlink=Carl Linnaeus | year=1766 | title=Systema naturae : per regna tria natura, secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis | edition=12th | volume=Volume 1, Part 1 | publisher=Laurentii Salvii  | place=Holmiae (Stockholm) | language=Latin | page=336 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/42946532 }}</ref> The [[type location (biology)|type location]] was subsequently corrected to [[Puducherry]] in southern India.<ref>{{ cite book | editor1-last=Mayr | editor1-first=Ernst | editor1-link=Ernst Mayr | editor2-last=Paynter | editor2-first=Raymond A. Jr | year=1964 | title=Check-list of Birds of the World | volume=Volume 10 | publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology  | place=Cambridge, Massachusetts  | pages=133\u2013134 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14486322 }}</ref> The [[Specific name (zoology)|specific name]] is from the Latin ''fulicatus'' for \"dusky\" or \"black\".<ref name=hbwkey>{{cite web | last=Jobling | first=J.A. | year=2018 | title= Key to Scientific Names in Ornithology | editor1-last=del Hoyo | editor1-first=J. | editor2-last=Elliott | editor2-first=A. | editor3-last=Sargatal | editor3-first=J. | editor4-last=Christie | editor4-first=D.A. | editor5-last=de Juana | editor5-first=E. | website=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive | publisher=Lynx Edicions | url=https://www.hbw.com/dictionary/definition/fulicata-fulicatus | accessdate=10 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe Indian robin was formerly placed in the [[monotypic]] genus ''Saxicoloides''. It was moved to ''[[Copsychus]]'' based on the results of [[molecular phylogenetic]] studies of birds in the family [[Muscicapidae]].<ref>{{ cite journal | last1=Sangster  | first1=G. | last2=Alstr\u00f6m | first2=P. | last3=Forsmark | first3=E. | last4=Olsson | first4=U. | year=2010 | title=Multi-locus phylogenetic analysis of Old World chats and flycatchers reveals extensive paraphyly at family, subfamily and genus level (Aves: Muscicapidae) | journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume=57 | issue=1 | pages=380\u2013392 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2010.07.008 | pmid=20656044}}</ref><ref>{{ cite journal | last1=Zuccon | first1=D. | last2=Ericson | first2=P.G.P. | year=2010 | title=A multi-gene phylogeny disentangles the chat-flycatcher complex (Aves: Muscicapidae) | journal=Zoologica Scripta  | volume=39 | issue=3 | pages=213\u2013224 | doi=10.1111/j.1463-6409.2010.00423.x }}</ref><ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | title=Chats, Old World flycatchers | website=World Bird List Version 6.2 | url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/chats/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union| accessdate=20 May 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Voelker|first=Gary|last2=Pe\u00f1alba|first2=Joshua V.|last3=Huntley|first3=Jerry W.|last4=Bowie|first4=Rauri C. K.|date=2014-04-01|title=Diversification in an Afro-Asian songbird clade (Erythropygia\u2013Copsychus) reveals founder-event speciation via trans-oceanic dispersals and a southern to northern colonization pattern in Africa|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution |volume=73|pages=97\u2013105|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2014.01.024|pmid=24508703}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Indian Robin (Saxicoloides fulicata) in Kawal, AP W IMG 2031.jpg|thumb|left|Male from Andhra Pradesh, showing features of ''intermedius'']]\nThe Indian robin is sexually dimorphic in plumage with the male being mainly black with a white shoulder patch or stripe whose visible extent can vary with posture. The northern populations have the upper plumage brownish while the southern populations are black above. The males have chestnut undertail coverts and these are visible as the bird usually holds the 6\u20138&nbsp;cm long tail raised upright. The females are brownish above, have no white shoulder stripe and are greyish below with the vent a paler shade of chestnut than the males. Birds of the northern populations are larger than those from southern India or Sri Lanka. Juvenile birds are much like females but the throat is mottled.<ref name=ras/>\n\nSeveral populations are named based on their plumage differences. The nominate subspecies refers to the population found across southern Peninsular India. Race ''leucopterus'' is found in [[Sri Lanka]]. Race ''cambaiensis'' of western India and ''erythrura''  (=''erythrurus'') of eastern India (south to around Sambalpur<ref>{{cite journal|author=Majumdar, N |year=1980| title= Occurrence of the Bengal Black Robin, ''Saxicoloides fulicata erythrura'' (Lesson) [Muscicapidae: Turdinae], and the Assam Purple Sunbird, ''Nectarinia asiatica intermedia'' (Hume) [Nectariniidae] in Orissa State| journal= J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc. |volume=77|issue=2|page=334|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/44708256}}</ref>) have the males with brown backs. The population ''intermedius'' includes forms between ''cambaiensis'', ''erythrura'' and ''fulicata'' in central India and parts of the Deccan region. A race ''munda'' was named on the basis of a specimen from Punjab but is now considered synonymous with ''cambaiensis''.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Van Tyne, J.  |author2=W. Koelz|year=1936|title=Seven new birds from the Punjab|journal=Occ. Pap. Mus. Zool. Univ. Michigan|volume=334|pages=5}}</ref> Older classifications treat the population in southern India under the name ''ptymatura'' while considering the type locality as Sri Lanka<ref name=whistler>{{cite book|title=Popular Handbook of Indian Birds|edition= 3rd|author=Hugh Whistler|year=1941|publisher=Gurney and Jackson|pages=104\u2013106|url=https://archive.org/stream/popularhandbooko033226mbp#page/n141/mode/2up}}</ref> although the type locality has subsequently been restricted to Pondicherry.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Ripley, SD|url=http://www.peabody.yale.edu/scipubs/bulletins_postillas/ypmP013_1952.pdf|year=1952|journal=Postilla|volume=13|title=The Thrushes|pages=1\u201348|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100627030143/http://www.peabody.yale.edu/scipubs/bulletins_postillas/ypmP013_1952.pdf|archivedate=2010-06-27}}</ref>\n\nLocal names recorded by [[Thomas C. Jerdon|Jerdon]] include ''Nalanchi'' (Telugu), ''Wannatikuruvi'' (Tamil, ''Washerman bird''), ''Kalchuri'' (Hindi) and ''Paan kiriththaa'' (Sinhala).<ref>{{cite book|title=The Birds of India. Volume 2 (part 1)|author=Jerdon, T. C.|year=1863|publisher=Military Orphan Press, Calcutta|pages=[https://archive.org/details/birdsofindiabein21jerd/page/121 121]|url=https://archive.org/details/birdsofindiabein21jerd}}</ref> The genus name indicates that it looks similar to ''Saxicola'', the genus of the [[pied bushchat]], a bird often found in similar habitats.\n[[File:Thar Bird.jpg|alt=Male fulicatus from Tharparkar, Sindh|left|thumb|Male from [[Tharparkar]], Sindh, Pakistan]]\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThis bird is found in open stony, grassy and scrub forest habitats. They are mainly found in dry habitats and are mostly absent from the thicker forest regions and high rainfall areas. All populations are resident and non-migratory. The species is often found close to human habitation and will frequently perch on rooftops.<ref name=ras>{{cite book|year=2005|title=Birds of South Asia: The Ripley Guide. Volume 2|page=396|publisher= Smithsonian Institution and Lynx Edicions|author1=Rasmussen PC  |author2=Anderton, JC }}</ref><ref name=whistler/>\n\nThe species was introduced into the New York region but did not establish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fws.gov/migratorybirds/issues/nonnative/Final%20NonNative%20Species%20List.pdf|title=Notices - Federal Register - March 15, 2005 Vol. 70, No. 49|author=USFWS|publisher=US Fish and Wildlife Service|date=2005-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Bull, J.|year=1974|title=Birds of New York state|publisher=American Museum of Natural History, New York}}</ref> A vagrant or escape has been noted from the Maldives.<ref name=ras/>\n\n==Ecology==\nPopulation densities of 193-240 individuals per square km have been estimated in the Pondicherry University campus. The ratio of males to females was about 1.5:1. Territory size for males is estimated at about 6650 m<sup>2</sup>.<ref>{{cite book|author=Rajasekhar, B|year=1993|chapter=Use of line transects to estimate Indian Robin (''Saxicoloides fulicata'') population at Pondicherry University Campus|title=Bird Conservation: Strategies for the Nineties and Beyond|editor=Verghese, A|editor2=Sridhar, S|editor3=Chakravarthy, AK| publisher=Ornithological Society of India, Bangalore|pages=191| chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/BirdConservationStrategies/BirdConservationIndia#page/n217/mode/1up}}.</ref> Males can be aggressive to others during the breeding season and will even attack reflections.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Wikramanayake, EB|year=1952|title=Blackbacked Robin attacking car|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=50|issue=3|page=656|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48057259}}</ref> Human activities such as felling and firewood removal in forests appear to benefit them.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Conservation and Society|pages=562\u2013591|volume=4|issue=4|year=2006|title=Consequences of Rural Biomass Extraction for Bird Communities in an Indian Tropical Dry Forest and the Role of Vegetation Structure|author1=Kumar, Raman|author2=Shahabuddin, Ghazala|url=http://www.conservationandsociety.org/cs_4_4_4-562.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070821082742/http://www.conservationandsociety.org/cs_4_4_4-562.pdf|archivedate=2007-08-21}}</ref>\n\n===Food===\nThey feed mostly on insects but are known to take frogs and lizards especially when feeding young at the nest.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Sivasubramanian, C|year=1991|title=Frog and lizard in the dietary of the Indian Robin ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' (Linn.)|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=88|issue=3|page=458|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48673894}}</ref> Individuals may forage late in the evening to capture insects attracted to lights.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Bharos, A. M. K.|year=1997|title=Indian Robin ''Saxicola fulicata'' foraging in the light of fluorescent lamps|journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society|volume=94|page=571|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48601949}}</ref>\n\n===Breeding===\n[[File:Indian Robin bird (Saxicoloides fulicatus) Nest and Eggs 01.JPG|thumb|right|Nest with eggs.]]\nThe breeding season is December to September but varies according to region and usually begins with the first rains.<ref name=betts/> Peak breeding in northern India is in June<ref name=oates/> and is earlier in Southern India.<ref name=betts/> In Sri Lanka it breeds in March to June and August to September.<ref name=ras/> Males sing during this season and display by lowering and spreading their tail feathers and strutting around the female, displaying their sides and fluffing their undertail coverts.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Thyagaraju, A. S.|year=1955|title=The courtship (?) display of the Blackbacked Indian Robin [''Saxicoloides fulicata'' (Linn.)]|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc. |volume=53|issue=1|pages=129\u2013130|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48180511}}</ref> The songs of males have variants for inviting mates and for deterring other males.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Breeding biology of Indian Robin ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' in northern India|author=Kumar, A|url= http://connectjournals.com/file_full_text/1300001H_7.pdf| year=2012| journal=J. Exp. Zool. India|volume=15| issue=1|pages=57\u201361}}</ref> Males will drive away other males and patrol their territory by flying with slow wing-beats from perch to perch. They may sometimes peck at their reflections.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Wikramanayake, E.B.|year=1952|title=Blackbacked robin [''Saxicoloides f. fulicata'' (Linn.)] attacking car|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=50|issue=3|page=656|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48057259}}</ref> An aggressive display involves fluffing up the feathers and holding the bill high.<ref name=hbk/>\n[[File:Indian Robin (Saxicoloides fulicata)- Male with feed for Immature W IMG 8064.jpg|thumb|left|Male feeding young ([[Parli, Maharashtra|Parli]], [[India]]).]]\nNests are built between rocks, in holes in walls or in a tree hollow.<ref>{{cite journal|year=1996|title=Peculiar nesting site and some observations on the breeding behaviour of Indian Robin ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' Linn|journal=[[Newsletter for Birdwatchers]] |volume=36|issue=1|pages=3\u20135|author1=Shanbhag, AB|author2=Gramopadhye, A|url=https://archive.org/stream/NLBW36_1#page/n1/mode/1up}}</ref> Nests are lined with animal hair and it has been noted that many nests have pieces of snake sloughs.<ref name=whistler/><ref>{{cite journal|journal=The Auk|volume = 43|issue= 4|year=1926| title= On the use, by birds, of snakes' sloughs as nesting material|author=Strecker, John K|url=http://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v043n04/p0501-p0507.pdf|pages=501\u2013507|doi=10.2307/4075138|jstor = 4075138}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://archive.org/stream/ibisns03brit#page/430/mode/2up/ | title=Notes on various Indian birds|author=Beavan, RC| authorlink=Robert Cecil Beavan|journal=Ibis| volume=3 | pages=430\u2013455|year=1867|issue=12|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1867.tb06443.x}}</ref> The eggs are of regular oval form, but many are elongated and a few pointed. They have a fair amount of gloss. The ground-colour is white, often tinged with faint green or pink, and this is rather closely spotted, speckled, streaked, and mottled, with rich reddish or umber-brown and brownish yellow, with some underlying lavender. The markings are denser at the larger end of the egg, where they form an irregular cap. Some eggs are blotched with dark reddish brown at the large end. Eggs are about {{convert|0.76|-|0.84|in|cm}} long and {{convert|0.55|-|0.62|in|cm}} wide.<ref name=oates>{{cite book|author=Oates, E W|year=1905 |title=Catalogue of the collection of birds' eggs in the British Museum |volume=4|pages=151\u2013153 |url=https://archive.org/stream/catalogueofcolle04brit#page/150/mode/2up}}</ref> Three to four eggs is the usual clutch.<ref>{{cite book|author=Oates, E. W. 1890|title=The Fauna of British India, Including Ceylon and Burma. Birds. Volume 2|date=1889-98|publisher=Taylor and Francis London| pages=[https://archive.org/details/birdsindia02oaterich/page/115 115]|url=https://archive.org/details/birdsindia02oaterich }}</ref> An abnormal clutch of seven has been noted although none of the eggs hatched at this nest.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Javed|first=Salim|year=1990|title=Abnormal clutch in Indian Brownbacked Robin ''Saxicoloides fulicata cambaiensis'' (Latham)|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=89|issue=2|page=258|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48732722}}</ref> Only the female incubates.<ref>{{cite book|author=Ali, S|year=1997|title=The Book of Indian Birds|edition=12th|isbn=978-0-19-563731-1|publisher=Oxford University Press|oclc=214935260}}</ref> Eggs hatch in about 10\u201312 days.<ref name=hbk>{{cite book|author1=Ali, S  |author2=S Dillon Ripley|pages=61\u201367|title=Handbook of the birds of India and Pakistan|volume=9|edition=2nd|year=1998|publisher=Oxford University Press}}</ref> Chicks have black down.<ref name=betts>{{cite journal|author=Betts, F N |year=1951| title=The birds of Coorg. Part 1 |journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc. |volume=50|issue=1|pages=20\u201363|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48056474}}</ref> Both males and females feed the young, the males sometimes passing food to the female which in turn feeds the young.<ref name=hbk/><ref>{{cite journal|author=George, JC |year=1961|title=Parental cooperation in the feeding of nestlings in the Indian Robin|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=58|issue=1|pages=267\u2013268|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/47540817}}</ref> Nestlings may feign dead ([[thanatosis]]) when handled.<ref name=hbk/> Nestlings may be preyed on by the [[rufous treepie]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Begbie, A|year=1905|title=Nest of the Brown-backed Indian Robin ''Thamnobia cambaiensis''|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=16|issue=3|page=513|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/5725855}}</ref> The same nest site may be reused in subsequent years.<ref name=hbk/><ref>{{cite journal|author= Naik, RM |year=1963| title= On the nesting habits of the Indian Robin, ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' (Linnaeus)|journal=[[Newsletter for Birdwatchers]] |volume=3| issue=9|page=7|url=https://archive.org/stream/NLBW3#page/n139/mode/1up}}</ref>\n\nAn old anecdotal record of these birds laying their eggs in the nests of ''[[Turdoides]]'' babblers has not been supported by later observers.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Field, F|year=1902|title=Robin laying in babbler's nest|journal=J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=14|issue=3|pages=610\u2013611|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/30158289}}</ref> Laboratory studies have demonstrated cyclic changes in the [[melanin]] pigmentation of the tissue surrounding the testes. The dark pigmentation is lost during the breeding season and regained later.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Poult. Sci.|year=1983|volume=62|issue=2|pages=385\u2013388|title=Instance of melanosis in the gonads of male Indian Robin, ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' (Lin)|vauthors=Agrawal SC, Bansal G |pmid=6835913|doi=10.3382/ps.0620385|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n===Parasites===\nSeveral parasites including a [[cestode]] have been identified in this species.<ref>{{cite journal|title=A new avian cestode from ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' at Aurangabad (M.S.) India|vauthors=Shinde GB, Gharge MD, Gavhane AB, Jadhav BV |journal=[[Rivista di Parassitologia]]|year=1990|volume=51|issue=3|pages=255\u2013257}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=''Haemaphysalis kutchensis'' sp. n., a Common Larval and Nymphal Parasite of Birds in Northwestern India (Ixodoidea, Ixodidae)|author1=Harry Hoogstraal |author2=Harold Trapido |journal=The Journal of Parasitology|volume=49|issue=3|date=1 June 1963|pages=489\u2013497|doi=10.2307/3275824|issn=0022-3395|jstor=3275824}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n==Other sources==\n{{refbegin}}\n* George, JC (1963) Some observations on the breeding behaviour of the Indian Robin, ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' (Linnaeus). Pavo 1(2):71-78.\n* Magon, VK (1979) Distribution of acid phosphatase in the digestive system of two Indian birds, ''Uroloncha malabarica'' and ''Saxicoloides fulicata''. Pavo 17(1&2):27-32.\n* Rajvanshi, G; Gupta, MM; Yeshowardhana; Singh, VS. (1985) Histochemical localization of calcium and iron in the gonad of male Indian Robin (''Saxicoloides fulicata''). Pavo 23(1&2):31-36.\n* Rajvanshi, G; Gupta, MM; Bhatnagar, VK; Bhatnagar, Sumar (1985) Cyclic changes in Carbohydrate localization in gonad of male Indian Robin ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' (Linn.). Pavo 23(1&2):41-46.\n* Gupta, MM; Rajvanshi, G; Singh, VS. (1986) Histochemical localization of proteins and Tryptophane aminoacid in testis of Indian Robin ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' (Linn.). Pavo 24(1&2):69-76.\n* {{cite journal|author=Culshaw, JC|year=1948|title=Some observations on the territories of Blackbacked Indian Robins ''Saxicoloides fulicata fulicata'', Linn|journal=Jour. Bengal Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=22|issue=3|pages=92}}\n*{{cite journal|author=Stonor, CR|year=1944|title= On the display of the Indian Robin, ''Saxicoloides fulicata'' (Linnaeus)|journal=Ibis|volume=86|issue=1|pages=91\u201393|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1944.tb07534.x}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Copsychus fulicatus}}\n* [http://ibc.lynxeds.com/species/indian-robin-saxicoloides-fulicatus Internet Bird Collection]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1591245|from2=Q27075634}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:robin, Indian}}\n[[Category:Copsychus|Indian robin]]\n[[Category:Robins|Indian robin]]\n[[Category:Birds of India]]\n[[Category:Birds of South Asia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1766|Indian robin]]\n", "name_user": "Shyamal", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_robin"}
{"title_page": "Shayan Italia", "text_new": "{{short description|British pop singer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name        = Shayan Italia\n| image       = Shayan Italia at his home in Bandra West, Mumbai, India.jpg\n| caption     = Italia at his home\n| background  = solo_singer\n| birth_name  = \n| alias       = \n| birth_date  = \n| birth_place = [[Secunderabad, Andhra Pradesh]], India\n| instrument  = [[Piano]]\n| genre       = [[Adult contemporary music|Adult contemporary]], [[Pop music|pop]]\n| occupation  = Entrepreneur, musician, singer-songwriter\n| website     = {{URL|shayanitalia.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Shayan Italia''' is an Indian-born entrepreneur, pianist and songwriter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/071007/International/international00007.html|title=Wannabee star uses eBay to launch pop career|website=www.sundaytimes.lk|access-date=2018-08-26}}</ref> He was the first person to sell a portion of his future earnings on [[eBay]]<ref>{{cite news|author=Ayushi Uberoi|title=Meet Shayan Italia|publisher=The Viewspaper|date=4 May 2008|url=http://theviewspaper.net/meet-shayan-italia\u2026/}}</ref> and with his song \"Reflection\". On 20 September 2018, he was awarded the \"Global Indian Of The Year\" by [[Mid Day]].<ref name=\"Indian Express\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.indulgexpress.com/culture/music/2018/nov/02/hyderabad-born-pianist-shayan-italia-on-his-record-breaking-rendition-of-the-indian-national-anthem-10939.html|title=Hyderabad-born pianist Shayan Italia talks about his record-breaking rendition of the Indian national anthem and making 'real' music|date=2018-11-02|work=Indian Express|access-date=2018-11-02|language=en}}</ref> Italia's wellness startup app \"START\" launches in 2020 that will help individuals increase their focus, immunity and energy levels. His debut [[Hindi]] song \"#ShaLaLaLa\" and musical short film of the same name is set to launch on [[YouTube]], featuring visuals shot in 4K by Italian cinematographer Gianni Giannelli.\n\nCreated for 15 August 2019, [[Independence Day (India)]] celebrating 71 years, Italia's piano version of the Indian National Anthem acquired over 100 million views during the Independence week on [[YouTube]]. It is currently the most viewed rendition of the [[Indian National Anthem]] and any national anthem globally online till date. \n\n== Education ==\nItalia studied at [[The Doon School]] in [[Dehradun]] and earned a bachelor's degree in international trade from [[Osmania University]], followed by a bachelor's degree in [[audio engineering]] from the Alchemea College of Audio Engineering, and then a master's degree in business management from [[University of Westminster]].<ref name=\"rocks\" />\n\n==Music==\nHe began writing songs after his mother died,<ref name=\"rocks\"/> and was the first unsigned act to have a song played on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' and performed at the [[Royal Albert Hall]].<ref name=\"RAH\">{{cite news | last = Smith| first = David| title = Debut album for singer who sold himself online| newspaper = [[The Guardian]]| date = 26 August 2007| url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2007/aug/26/musicnews.music| accessdate = 2009-08-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/film-and-tv/curtain-falls-in-true-bollywood-splendour-1014529|title=Curtain falls in true Bollywood splendour at Shilpa Shetty\u2019s finale stage performance|last=News|first=Manchester Evening|date=2007-12-19|work=men|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> To support the production of his album \"Feel\", he auctioned off a portion of his future earnings on [[eBay]], raising US$18,000 in seven days from three individuals residing in three continents. Later, he raised a sum total of US$1 million by conventional means. He has also been interviewed by [[David Frost|Sir David Frost]] on his show [[Frost Over The World]]<ref name=\"RAH\" /> His song \"Reflection\" reached number one on YouTube's music video chart.<ref>{{cite news| last = Sabbagh| first = Dan | title = YouTube No 1 is a long way from success on the music charts| newspaper = [[The Times]]| date = 13 March 2008| url = https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/youtube-no-1-is-a-long-way-from-success-on-the-music-charts-nqflrw55m89| accessdate = 2009-08-02}}</ref> The song had previously won the All India Song Contest.<ref>{{cite news|last=Momin|first=Sajeda|title=In the mood for a melody|newspaper=[[DNA (newspaper)|Daily News and Analysis]]|date=9 February 2008|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/lifestyle/salon_in-the-mood-for-a-melody_1149884|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref> Italia does not actively tour even though he has performed at selected venues across the world. In 2020, his debut Hindi song release is lined up for release.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Biryani360==\nItalia started ''Biryani360'' in [[Mumbai]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Purva Mehra|title=FOOD REVIEW: BIRYANI 360|publisher=\u2018\u2019The Daily Pao\u2019\u2019|date=15 March 2015|url=http://www.thedailypao.com/food-review-biryani-360/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B7PWTwzgoXzXMkdaeTJ0WmNSenM/view|title=Biryani360 leads food startups explosion in India.pdf|work=Google Docs|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref> The flagship kitchen is in in [[Bandra]], a popular district of [[Mumbai]]. The startup used BlueFlame technology to create food that was low in oil and cholesterol.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/mumbai/others/Mirror-review-The-slim-biryani/articleshow/44805654.cms|title=Mirror review: The slim biryani|work=Mumbai Mirror|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/exec-life/food/biryani-in-mumbai-gets-a-360-degree-makeover-150417|title=Biryani in Mumbai gets a 360 degree makeover|date=2015-04-17|work=Indian Television Dot Com|access-date=2018-08-25|language=en}}</ref> Biryani360 was sold in March 2016.\n\n== START ==\nItalia's wellness startup app \"START\" launches in 2020, helping individuals increase their focus, immunity and energy levels.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Philanthropy ==\nItalia helps to raise money for cancer research and multiple sclerosis treatment in the memory of his parents.<ref name=\":0\" /> He has helped raise INR 1,000 crore (approximately US$135 million) till date.<ref name=\"Indian Express\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nItalia lost his mother to [[Multiple myeloma]] and father, to [[Multiple sclerosis]] when he was young. Born and raised a Zoroastrian<ref>{{cite press release|title=Indian-born singer/songwriter to take UK charts by storm|date=31 October 2007|publisher=Great Reporter|url=http://www.greatreporter.com/content/indian-born-singer-set-take-uk-charts-storm|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref> in [[Secunderabad]], India, Italia moved to London after the deaths of both his parents.<ref name=\"rocks\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/10/12/stories/2007101259480200.htm|title=This Hyderabadi rocks in U.K.|author=Abhijit Dev Kumar|date=12 October 2007|accessdate=2009-09-06|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref>  His first cousin is [[Karan Bilimoria, Baron Bilimoria|Lord Bilimoria of Chelsea]] and his uncle is Ratan Batliboi, a widely popular architect and the Chairman of the board at [[Child Rights and You]] (CRY).<ref name=\"Indian Express\"/><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/global-envy-national-pride-shayan-italia/19795180|title=Global envy, national pride: Shayan Italia|date=2018-09-11|work=mid-day|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and Recognition ==\n\n# Global Indian Of The Year 2018 <ref name=\"Indian Express\"/>\n# Honorary Award Winner - Great American Songwriting Contest (2004)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greatamericansong.com/honorary2004.html|title=Great American Song Honorary Awards|website=www.greatamericansong.com|access-date=2018-08-09}}</ref>\n# All India Song Contest Winner (2006)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/lifestyle/salon-in-the-mood-for-a-melody-1149884|title=In the mood for a melody|date=2008-02-09|work=dna|access-date=2018-08-09|language=en-US}}</ref>\n# Editors Choice Award Winner - International Poetry Competition (2007)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.femalefirst.co.uk/music/popmusic/single/Shayan+Italia+Reflection-3368.html|title=Shayan Italia 'Reflection'|access-date=2018-08-09|language=en}}</ref>\n#First Unsigned Music Artist to Appear on BBC Radio 4's Desert Island Discs (2007)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/aug/26/musicnews.music|title=Debut album for singer who sold himself online|last=Smith|first=David|date=2007-08-25|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-08-09}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.shayanitalia.com/ Shayan Italia Official Website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shayan Italia}}\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Westminster]]\n[[Category:The Doon School alumni]]\n[[Category:English pop singers]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Indian Zoroastrians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Hyderabad, India]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British pop singer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name        = Shayan Italia\n| image       = Shayan Italia at his home in Bandra West, Mumbai, India.jpg\n| caption     = Italia at his home\n| background  = solo_singer\n| birth_name  = \n| alias       = \n| birth_date  = \n| birth_place = [[Secunderabad, Andhra Pradesh]], India\n| instrument  = [[Piano]]\n| genre       = [[Adult contemporary music|Adult contemporary]], [[Pop music|pop]]\n| occupation  = Entrepreneur, musician, singer-songwriter\n| website     = {{URL|shayanitalia.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Shayan Italia''' is an International multi-award winning Indian-born entrepreneur, pianist and songwriter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/071007/International/international00007.html|title=Wannabee star uses eBay to launch pop career|website=www.sundaytimes.lk|access-date=2018-08-26}}</ref> He came into the limelight by becoming the first person to sell a portion of his future earnings on [[eBay]]<ref>{{cite news|author=Ayushi Uberoi|title=Meet Shayan Italia|publisher=The Viewspaper|date=4 May 2008|url=http://theviewspaper.net/meet-shayan-italia\u2026/}}</ref> and with his song \"Reflection\". On 20 September 2018 he was awarded the \"Global Indian Of The Year\" by [[Mid Day]].<ref name=\"Indian Express\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.indulgexpress.com/culture/music/2018/nov/02/hyderabad-born-pianist-shayan-italia-on-his-record-breaking-rendition-of-the-indian-national-anthem-10939.html|title=Hyderabad-born pianist Shayan Italia talks about his record-breaking rendition of the Indian national anthem and making 'real' music|date=2018-11-02|work=Indian Express|access-date=2018-11-02|language=en}}</ref> Italia's wellness startup app \"START\" launches in 2020 helping individuals increase their focus, immunity and energy levels by 2-3X in just 7 days, alongside reducing stress, without any change to one's diet or exercise using science at a cellular level <ref name=\":0\" />. His debut [[Hindi]] song \"#ShaLaLaLa\" and musical short film of the same is set to launch on [[YouTube]] featuring groundbreaking visuals shot in 4K Ultra HD by Internationally acclaimed Italian cinematographer Gianni Giannelli.\n\nCreated for 15 August 2019, [[Independence Day (India)]] celebrating 71 years, Italia's piano version of the Indian National Anthem acquired over 100 million views during the Independence week on [[YouTube]]. It is currently the most viewed rendition of the [[Indian National Anthem]] and any national anthem globally online till date. #IWouldStandForThis and #71for71Challenge are global initiatives that honour the [[Indian National Anthem]], performed by Italia in [[8K resolution]] on the [[Steinway D-274]] concert grand piano, paying tribute to his mother, who died of cancer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deccanchronicle.com/lifestyle/viral-and-trending/070818/ode-to-the-motherland.html|title=Ode to the Motherland|date=2018-08-07|work=Deccan Chronicle|access-date=2018-08-25|language=en}}</ref> The #71for71Challenge trended on Twitter for 2 days.<ref name=\":0\" /> The music rendition brings together multinational cross-cultural music and video production talent from all over the world to inspire patriotism among the youth of India in its digital age. The video is directed by Dr. Farhad Vijay Arora. It is the first music video to be fully processed in [[8K resolution]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/secunderabad-boy-shayan-italia-wins-over-the-internet-with-his-rendition-of-the-national-anthem/articleshow/65414127.cms|title=Secunderabad boy Shayan Italia wins over the Internet with his rendition of the national anthem - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/piano-rendition-of-jana-gana-mana-crosses-77-mn-views-on-youtube-becomes-most-viewed-national-anthem-4969751.html|title=Piano rendition of Jana Gana Mana crosses 77 mn views on YouTube, becomes most viewed national anthem- Entertainment News, Firstpost|work=Firstpost|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/trending/viral-videos-trending/pianist-playing-the-national-anthem-viral-video-5306715/|title=Independence Day 2018: This pianist playing the National Anthem has gone viral with over 72 million views|date=2018-08-14|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/the-buzz/article/independence-day-jana-gana-mana-15-august-2018-shayan-italia-national-anthem-record-71-million-views-youtube-video/269476|title=Shayan Italia's heartfelt version of 'Jana Gana Mana' breaks national anthem records, crosses 71 million views|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thequint.com/neon/social-buzz/71-for-71-challenge-national-anthem|title=Here\u2019s Why \u201871 For 71 Challenge\u2019 Is Trending on Twitter|work=The Quint|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mumbaidaily.in/story/43896/blazing-past-50-million-youtube-views-viral-shayan-italia-jana-gana-mana-video-strikes-patriotic-chord.html|title=Blazing past 50 million YouTube views, viral Shayan Italia Jana Gana Mana video strikes patriotic chord {{!}} Mumbai Daily|website=www.mumbaidaily.in|language=en-US|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nItalia studied at [[The Doon School]] in [[Dehradun]] and has earned three degrees: a bachelor's degree in International Trade Practices and Procedures from [[Osmania University]], a bachelor's degree in [[audio engineering]] from the Alchemea College of Audio Engineering, and a master's degree in Business Management from the [[University of Westminster]].<ref name=\"rocks\" />\n\n==Music==\nInitially, Italia set out to be a songwriter. He began writing songs after his mother died.<ref name=\"rocks\"/> He discovered the talent to sing while recording the demos of his two songs. He was the first unsigned act to have a song played on [[BBC Radio 4]]'s ''[[Desert Island Discs]]'' and performed at the [[Royal Albert Hall]].<ref name=\"RAH\">{{cite news | last = Smith| first = David| title = Debut album for singer who sold himself online| newspaper = [[The Guardian]]| date = 26 August 2007| url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2007/aug/26/musicnews.music| accessdate = 2009-08-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/whats-on/film-and-tv/curtain-falls-in-true-bollywood-splendour-1014529|title=Curtain falls in true Bollywood splendour at Shilpa Shetty\u2019s finale stage performance|last=News|first=Manchester Evening|date=2007-12-19|work=men|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref> To support the production of his album \"Feel\", he auctioned off a portion of his future earnings on [[eBay]], raising US$18,000 in seven days from three individuals residing in three continents. Later, he raised a sum total of US$1 million by conventional means. He has also been interviewed by [[David Frost|Sir David Frost]] on his show [[Frost Over The World]]<ref name=\"RAH\" /> His song \"Reflection\" reached number one on YouTube's music video chart.<ref>{{cite news| last = Sabbagh| first = Dan | title = YouTube No 1 is a long way from success on the music charts| newspaper = [[The Times]]| date = 13 March 2008| url = https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/youtube-no-1-is-a-long-way-from-success-on-the-music-charts-nqflrw55m89| accessdate = 2009-08-02}}</ref> The song had previously won the All India Song Contest.<ref>{{cite news|last=Momin|first=Sajeda|title=In the mood for a melody|newspaper=[[DNA (newspaper)|Daily News and Analysis]]|date=9 February 2008|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/lifestyle/salon_in-the-mood-for-a-melody_1149884|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref> Italia does not actively tour even though he has performed at selected venues across the world. In 2020, his debut Hindi song release is lined up for release.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Biryani360==\nItalia started ''Biryani360'' in [[Mumbai]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Purva Mehra|title=FOOD REVIEW: BIRYANI 360|publisher=\u2018\u2019The Daily Pao\u2019\u2019|date=15 March 2015|url=http://www.thedailypao.com/food-review-biryani-360/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B7PWTwzgoXzXMkdaeTJ0WmNSenM/view|title=Biryani360 leads food startups explosion in India.pdf|work=Google Docs|access-date=2018-08-21}}</ref> The idea came to him when he was sitting in his bedroom and fooling around with animation software and created a video of two fictitious characters that declared their unity for one another over their love for [[Biryani]]. This sparked interested among both family and peers and eventually led him to consider setting it up as a business.<ref>{{cite news|title=Basmati Baritone: Biryani360 Delivery Service|publisher=\u2018\u2019Brown Paper Bag\u2019\u2019|date=5 March 2015|url=http://brownpaperbag.in/mumbai/food-and-drink/briyani360}}</ref> The flagship kitchen was setup in [[Bandra]], a popular district of [[Mumbai]]. The startup used BlueFlame technology to create food that was low in oil and cholesterol.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/mumbai/others/Mirror-review-The-slim-biryani/articleshow/44805654.cms|title=Mirror review: The slim biryani|work=Mumbai Mirror|access-date=2018-08-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.indiantelevision.com/exec-life/food/biryani-in-mumbai-gets-a-360-degree-makeover-150417|title=Biryani in Mumbai gets a 360 degree makeover|date=2015-04-17|work=Indian Television Dot Com|access-date=2018-08-25|language=en}}</ref> Biryani360 started on 1 March 2015 and was sold in March 2016.\n\n== START ==\nItalia's wellness startup app \"START\" launches in 2020 helping individuals increase their focus, immunity and energy levels by 2-3X in just 7 days, alongside reducing stress. This is done at a cellular level without any change to one's diet or exercise.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Philanthropy ==\nItalia helps to raise money for cancer research and multiple sclerosis treatment in the memory of his parents.<ref name=\":0\" /> He has helped raise INR 1,000 crore (approximately US$135 million) till date. His now aims to shift his focus towards propelling education in India.<ref name=\"Indian Express\"/>\nstructure\n\n==Personal life==\nItalia lost his mother to [[Multiple myeloma]] and father, to [[Multiple sclerosis]] when he was young. Born and raised a Zoroastrian<ref>{{cite press release|title=Indian-born singer/songwriter to take UK charts by storm|date=31 October 2007|publisher=Great Reporter|url=http://www.greatreporter.com/content/indian-born-singer-set-take-uk-charts-storm|accessdate=2009-09-06}}</ref> in [[Secunderabad]], India, Italia moved to London after the deaths of both his parents.<ref name=\"rocks\">{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2007/10/12/stories/2007101259480200.htm|title=This Hyderabadi rocks in U.K.|author=Abhijit Dev Kumar|date=12 October 2007|accessdate=2009-09-06|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref>  His first cousin is [[Karan Bilimoria, Baron Bilimoria|Lord Bilimoria of Chelsea]] and his uncle is Ratan Batliboi, a widely popular architect and the Chairman of the board at [[Child Rights and You]] (CRY).<ref name=\"Indian Express\"/><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/global-envy-national-pride-shayan-italia/19795180|title=Global envy, national pride: Shayan Italia|date=2018-09-11|work=mid-day|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and Recognition ==\n\n# Global Indian Of The Year 2018 <ref name=\"Indian Express\"/>\n# Honorary Award Winner - Great American Songwriting Contest (2004)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greatamericansong.com/honorary2004.html|title=Great American Song Honorary Awards|website=www.greatamericansong.com|access-date=2018-08-09}}</ref>\n# All India Song Contest Winner (2006)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/lifestyle/salon-in-the-mood-for-a-melody-1149884|title=In the mood for a melody|date=2008-02-09|work=dna|access-date=2018-08-09|language=en-US}}</ref>\n# Editors Choice Award Winner - International Poetry Competition (2007)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.femalefirst.co.uk/music/popmusic/single/Shayan+Italia+Reflection-3368.html|title=Shayan Italia 'Reflection'|access-date=2018-08-09|language=en}}</ref>\n#First Unsigned Music Artist to Appear on BBC Radio 4's Desert Island Discs (2007)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/aug/26/musicnews.music|title=Debut album for singer who sold himself online|last=Smith|first=David|date=2007-08-25|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-08-09}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.shayanitalia.com/ Shayan Italia Official Website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shayan Italia}}\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Westminster]]\n[[Category:The Doon School alumni]]\n[[Category:English pop singers]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Indian Zoroastrians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Hyderabad, India]]\n", "name_user": "BahrdozsBulafka", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(-WP:Puffery,WP:Unencyclopedic)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shayan_Italia"}
{"title_page": "Chaltabagan Durga Puja", "text_new": "The '''Manicktala Chaltabagan Lohapatty Durga Puja ''' is a [[Durga Puja]] celebration in [[Kolkata]], [[India]]. It was founded in 1943 by Late Lakhi Chand Jaiswal as a small celebration in a shop<ref name=\"Wala Unveils\">{{cite news |url=http://www.newswala.com/India-National-News/Debasree-Roy-unveils-Durga-puja-show-16313.html |title=Debasree Roy unveils Durga puja show |date=September 3, 2012 |newspaper=NewsWala |access-date=August 31, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903135617/http://www.newswala.com/India-National-News/Debasree-Roy-unveils-Durga-puja-show-16313.html |archive-date=September 3, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and has grown into one of Kolkata's largest Durga Puja celebrations, attended by celebrities, industrialists, politicians and foreign diplomats.<ref name=\"ToI Glass\">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kolkata/Dream-in-glass-at-Chaltabagan/articleshow/9989179.cms |date=September 15, 2011 |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |title=Dream in glass at Chaltabagan |first=Sumati |last=Yengkhom}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Chalta Bagan Durga Puja 2019.jpg|thumb|Manicktalla Chaltabagan Lohapatty Durga Pujo 2019]]\n\nThe Durga Puja is held near the intersection of [[Vivekananda Road]] and [[Amherst Street (Kolkata)|Amherst Street]].<ref name=\"ToI Glass\" /> [[Environmentalism]] is a common theme of the Manicktala Chaltabagan Lohapatty Durga Puja, which used a [[windmill]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1131010/jsp/calcutta/story_17442475.jsp#.VAN6QmNagmV |title=Gen Y plays judge on pandal tour |date=October 10, 2013 |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (India)|The Telegraph]]}}</ref> and [[solar panel]]s to power the lighting.<ref name=\"ToI Glass\" /> \n\nThe committee organizing the Durga Puja is headed by President Late Lakhi Chand Jaiswal and Chairman sundeep Bhutoria.<ref name=\"Wala Unveils\" /> It has supported various charitable causes, including a donation of {{INR}}50,000 to disaster relief for victims of [[Cyclone Aila]] in 2009<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1090924/jsp/calcutta/story_11534774.jsp |title=Puja pick of right spirit |date=September 24, 2009 |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (India)|The Telegraph]]}}</ref> and {{INR}}100,000 towards the relief fund of [[Governor of West Bengal]] [[M. K. Narayanan]] in 2010.<ref name=\"Telegraph Potpourri\">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1121019/jsp/entertainment/story_16106433.jsp#.VAN6PGNagmV |title=Potpourri |date=October 19, 2012 |newspaper=[[The Telegraph (India)|The Telegraph]]}}</ref>\n\nThe Manicktalla Chaltabagan Lohapatty Durga Puja has won the [[Asian Paints Sharad Shamman]] award for Best Puja in 1997 and for Best Artisan (Nepal Pal and Gouranga Pal) in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://asianpaints.com/25yearsAPSS/last_years.html|title= All winners list|work=[[Asian Paints]]|accessdate=2009-09-29| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091003123908/http://asianpaints.com/25yearsAPSS/last_years.html| archivedate= 3 October 2009}}</ref> In 2010 it was introduced into the True Spirit Puja Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"Telegraph Potpourri\" />\n\n<gallery>\nFile:\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09bf\u0995\u09a4\u09b2\u09be \u099a\u09be\u09b2\u09a4\u09be\u09ac\u09be\u0997\u09be\u09a8 \u09a6\u09c2\u09b0\u09cd\u0997\u09be \u09aa\u09c2\u099c\u09be \u09e8\u09e6\u09e7\u09ec.jpg|2016\nFile:\u09ae\u09be\u09a8\u09bf\u0995\u09a4\u09b2\u09be \u099a\u09be\u09b2\u09a4\u09be\u09ac\u09be\u0997\u09be\u09a8 \u09a6\u09c2\u09b0\u09cd\u0997\u09be \u09aa\u09c2\u099c\u09be \u09e8\u09e6\u09e7\u09ed.jpg|2017\nFile:\u099a\u09be\u09b2\u09a4\u09be\u09ac\u09be\u0997\u09be\u09a8 \u09a6\u09c2\u09b0\u09cd\u0997\u09be \u09aa\u09c2\u099c\u09be \u09e8\u09e6\u09e7\u09ee.jpg|2018\nFile:\u099a\u09be\u09b2\u09a4\u09be\u09ac\u09be\u0997\u09be\u09a8 \u09a6\u09c2\u09b0\u09cd\u0997\u09be \u09aa\u09c1\u099c\u09cb \u09e8\u09e6\u09e7\u09ee \u09ae\u09a3\u09cd\u09a1\u09aa\u09b8\u099c\u09cd\u